document: Surf Life Saving Club:  is a well known surf beach. The beach is patrolled ng December to the Easter. The  SLSC was established in 1958.
Beach walk: From Sprout Creek, , ,  to the bottom of the  h there is approx 6 km of beach, featuring rolling surf and spectacular views of the Otway Ranges and e.

Rock pools: See what sort of shells and stones you can collect. Can you find a bright red sea star? You can see all sorts of sea vegetation, small fish and crabs. Look at the bird life, gulls and cormorants.
Sand dunes: The beautiful rolling sand dunes shape the beach. 2011 has seen significant erosion due to winter storms that have bought strong winds and big waves (up to 10 feet).
Painkalac Creek: The creek setes  from  and forms an inlet behind the sand dunes before it cuts through to the ocean. A great place to shelter from the wind and for er children to swim.

Rocks and caves under the  h: There are more rockpools and rocky outcrops to explore under the  h. This area is part of the marine nal park. This means that all wildlife is protected and cannot be removed.
playground and picnic ground: There is small skateboard ramp for children to ride their scooters or skateboards. There are also swings and other play equipment for children and a picnic area.
lower shops: Pick up a coffee, newspaper or Fish and Chips! To the left of the shops, on the other side of the river, kans can be seen in the early morning or at dusk.

Loutit Bay lookout: Return to Painkalac Creek inlet and walk to the grassed area on the left. At the  h bollard turn right and walk up the signed (steep) walking track. Enjoy panaromic views on your walk up.
Historical  and building: At the h is the original  for the h keeper. The  area was first settled in the 1840s. The first tourists arrived in 1919.
Split Point h: Follow the signs and continue up the walking track. Shipping along the Victorian coast was much safer once the combination of this and other hs at  and  were built.

1. Tramway signal box: Built in 1928 soon after the electrification of the ston St and St Kilda Rd cable tramways. Originally included female public toilets, roofed passenger waiting area, small store and staff toilets.

2.  Baths: Built in 1903, the design reflected the social conventions of the time. Men and women were segregated for all facilities; second class baths were in the basement, first class on the main floor.

3. Magistrates Court: Built on the site of the earlier Supreme Court, the building retains fittings from the earlier court including the Gothic canopy that judge Sir  Barry sat under ng Ned  trial in 1880.
4. Old  Gaol: Built between 1851 - 1864. As the oldest surviving penal establishment, it was the site where Ned  was imprisoned, executed and buried, amongst many other criminals.

5. Eight Hour Day Monument: Built in 1923, the monument commemorates the Eight Hour Day movement started by stonemasons in 1856 to improve working cions - eight hours labour, eight hours rest and eight hours recreation.
6. Trades : Built in stages from 1873 - 1926, Trades  is of historical and social significance as a centre of radical and working class politics and activism in Victoria for over 100 rs.
7. Medley : Built in 1893 as a private residence, the building has since hd the In Club, In Consulate and for  time was used for a 'less reputable purpose'.
8. Lygon shop corner: Lygon Buildings is architecturally significant as the largest and most intact terrace of nineteenth century shops in . There are no other comble retail structures in .
9. Matthais H: A two storeyed stucco faced bstone h of 1865-6 with many charming and unusual features - a tower and weathervane, a cantilevered cast iron balcony and delicately glazed arched windows.
10. Sacred Heart Cic Church: Built in 1855-56. In the 1930s and 1940s the Church of the Sacred Heart became a primary focus for Carlton's In community, and this continued into the 1960s.
11. IMAX Theatre: IMAX is the world's largest cinema format, with a screen up to eight storeys high. Films, from documentaries to latest release movies, can be experienced in 2D or 3D.
12.  Museum: The museum has eight galleries, including one just for children. Highs include a complete skel of a b w, the aka Aboriginal Cultural Centre, a living rain and Phar Lap.
13. Royal Exhibition Building: The Royal Exhibition Building is the only surviving Great  that once hd a 19th-century internal exhibition and is still used for exhibitions.

14. Carlton Gardens: Developed in 19th-century Gardenesque style, the Gardens feature symmetrically-placed garden beds, significant avenues, the path system, specimen and clusters of trees, 2 small lakes and 3 s.
15. Playground: Wonderful playground with swings, slides and many opportunities to climb and cl, plus small hills to roll down!
16. Carlton Gardens Primary School: The school is an In Gothic style building built in 1884 with a hipped roof central pavilion buttressed either end by sly projecting .
17. Terrace Hs (201 - 205  Street): Built in 1884, Holcombe Terrace is a fine example of boom style terrace architecture and notable among the works of Norman Hitchcock.
18. Museo Ino: Museo Ino displays and interprets the experience of In migration, and the culture created by Ins in ia.

19. La Mama Theatre: Built in 1883, the building was used for various industrial purposes. In 1967, it was leased by Betty Burstall, teacher and theatre-lover, for use as a small theatre to nurture new ian drama.

19. Underground public toilets: The underground public toilets, built in 1939, are one of eleven built in  in response to public demand for public toilet facilities in  that were both sanitary and discreet.

21. 313-315  Street: Built in 1889, the buliding is architecturally significant for its highly unusual grotesque Gothic facade. The kan-gryphon grotesques on the pet are highly unusual and distinctive.
22. Carlton Court H: The Carlton Court H is historically significant as part of the civic core of  Street. It is directly opposite the 1878 Carlton Police Station.
The  Wharf:  Wharf has been a vital part of the town and inland river transport system since the 1880s. It was established by the  Progress Committee in 1888 to assist the burgeoning river trade.
Railway overpass: A  walk across the railway overpass leads to  Ave or head left down to the  King Drive underpass to avoid the stairs.
Prince and Princess of Wales  Plaza: This  is very special as it was opened by the Prince and Princess of Wales on the 29th October 1985. Many  residence crowded around to see the Princess Diana.

War Memorial : To the left is a War Memorial commemorating those who served in Vietnam, Korea
and South East Asia.

Sculpture commemorating Alfred , Primie Minister of ia and the initiator of the : Sculpted by Michael Meszaros and presented to the  to mark the centenary of the irrigation colony in 1987. The memorial represents  fruit bs and irrigation channels as seen from the air.
The G Hotel (to the right): Enter the G Hotel’s main entrance and turn left. To your right, you will see a display of historical photos. Through the glass doors are one of ’s original  s.
Commodore Motel former site of the  bo h: Back in 1888, this site was a early bo h called the . A plaque marking the site can be found at  to the motel’s restaurant. The  was demolished in 1965.
WIN TV: Originally STV8, opening in 1966 and next door is the Sunraysia Daily, the local newspaper.

The Cultivator: ’s earliest newspaper was the Cultivator, begun in 1888. It was a
twice-weekly publication that moved to the current Sunraysia Daily site at
22  Avenue in 1912.

Sunraysia Daily: Local identity, C.J De Garis bought The Cultivator along with the 
Telegraph and  Irrigationist and merged them into one paper, the
Sunraysia Daily, in 1920.

George and William  Building: Across the road is a single story late Victorian, red brick building, with
a brick and iron palisade fence. The building was gifted to La T Uni in 2009 by  Carrazza.

Electric Supply Department Substation No.1: In the centre plantation, stands the Electric Supply Department Substation No.1, dating back to 1936, when the production of electri was considered a local responsibility, rather than a state one.
Queen  II visit to ,  25th, 1954: When Queen  toured  in 1954, a decorative dais was erected in this area of the plantation.  Pics of this day are displayed at the  Centre. Visit to Barclays B in

Bowring's Store, corner  Avenue and 8th Street - Circa 1937: The site of the ANZ Bank was previously known as Bowring Corner and was the site of Bowring’s Store, opened in 1888. It extended into Langtree Avenue in 1961 but ceased business two decades later.

Old  Post Office (LHS of  Ave): This corner building was for over a century, the  Post Office. The earliest Post Office on this site was built in 1890, with much of the current building being erected in 1923.

George V Memorial  (in centre plantation): Cng into the centre plantation, you will find the George V Memorial , originally erected in the gardens of the Rio , home of W.B , it was moved to its current position in 1936

Law Courts (LHS of  Ave): Opened by rt Hulls, Victoria’s Attorney General, on Nov 23 2004. This complex was built on the site that n as Washington Stores, before becoming Maples, before it all went up in flames in 1996

70  Avenue (LHS of  Ave): Once the site of the Shire Offices, beginning as a modest, timber, two roomed building before the current building was erected in 1922. In 1971, the Shire Offices were relocated to Irymple.

Centre - Home to the Historical and Genealogical Societies (LHS of  Ave): Constructed in 1908, as the  Library, courtesy of a 2000 pound  made by Andrew , in 1906, after a request from Lord Hopetoun. The tower was added in 1922 as a soldier memorial.
Civic Buildings  (LHS of  Ave): The Civic Buildings, opened in 1958 and it’s also the site of the original Shire , also known as the  Town .
Statue of W.B.  (in center  plantation): In the center  plantation is a statue of W.B. , who died in 1926. The Paul Mountford sculpture was unveiled in 1929. A sir sculpture can be found in , SA.
Rotunda (in center  plantation): The centre  plantation is home to the  Rotunda, named for Cr George , former Shire President, who died whilst in office in 1913.

61  Ave - 's earliest surviving building (RHS of  Ave): On the RHS of  Ave is the earliest surviving building in . It started out as ’s first general store, owned by H.B , in 1887. A bank altered the building appearance in 1937.

69  Ave (RHS of  Ave): Built in 1914, this  Edian building has been a restaurant, a bank, a real estate agency and other businesses, which although altered over the rs, still retains some of its original charm.
Club (RHS of  Ave): The  "Gentlemen's Club" n in 1890 with Lord Ranfurly as the first President. Meetings were originally held at the Coffee Palace, until this building was completed in 1920.

Cinema Complex  (RHS of  Ave): The  Cinema complex was  established in 1975. A point of interest is that the cinema includes the original site of the Masonic Temple, built in 1907, with the façade still remaining.

Workingmans Club (LHS of  Ave): An iconic landmark, once famous for having the world’s longest bar (which was removed in recent vations.). Begun in 1908, it was originally a 1 story structure with a 2nd level added in 1935.

Workingmans Club  War Memorial (LHS of  Ave): Has stood at the front of the club, since 1920, honoring ’s war dead. The marble soldier is the work of A.D Thomson and the three-sided list of soldiers’ names underpins the heavy losses of WW1

Methodist Church (LHS of  Ave): Opened in 1912, this unique church had a number of architectural infnces, including Byzantine, Queen Anne, Masonic and Art Nouveau . Image: Methodist Church under construction 1911.

The Church of Christ  (RHS of  Ave): Built in 1908, the Church of Christ was first organised by Reuben Mansell in 1890 and members met in a variety of venues until this building was completed using all voluntary labour.
War Memorial (centre plantation): Commemorates those who died or were killed in World War One. Erected by the  Branch R. S. & S. I. L. A.

Uniting Church / St Andrew’s  (RHS of  Ave): The Uniting Church, known as St Andrew’s, started out as a Presbyterian church and was built in 1914, at a cost of 2097 pounds. It replaced a wooden structure that had been there since 1891.

St Margaret’s Anglican Church (LSH of  Ave): This church opened in 1902, with the addition of the sanctuary in 1934 and the vestry and bell tower in 1957 that honours the lost soldiers of World War II.

Madden Avenue : Madden Ave was originally planned to be the principal retail district of  due to easy access to the wharf. However,  Langtree, with it’s proximity to the railway proved to be more significant
RSL Sub Branch: The Returned and Services League with some 1500 Sub Branches ia wide and with a membership of 240,000 is the largest service association in ia.
Water Tower: As you cross over 10th street, to your right you will see one of  's Water Towers. Built in 1957, the tower provides water pressure for thousands of homes across the urban area.
Mecure Hotel : Commercial Hotel, commonly remembered as the Wintersun and now the Mecure Hotel was built in 1925

Disused water tower: Behind the hotel is a disused water tower, which from 1912 until 1957 operated as ’s sole source of water storage. Instigated by the former First  Irrigation Trust. 180000 litre capa
Under the Cs: 's well known and iconic meeting place is under the cs at  Street Station. Sit on the steps and see the world go by.
Mirka Mora mosaic: Mirka Mora made this mosaic in about 1985, it is brilliant. Do not be one of the thousands who walk past it every day without stopping.
To Birrarung Marr: The slope down to Birrarung Marr, always fills with expectation. The sculpture of hundreds of red poles is a cracker. Go up and push the poles firmly, what a noise!
Square: There always seems to be something happening at Fed Square whether it is concerts, buskers, festivals or people lolling about. The pavers are great to sit on on a sunny afternoon.
The Art Centre from Fed Square: Looking over to the Art Centre spire from Fed Square.
Birrarung Marr playground: The playground is always open. Watch kids play and enjoy the tube slides, sand pits, swinging hammocks, activity panels, rock and rope climbing features and balance beams.
Art Play: Art Play is a great place for children it has lots of shows and creative activities for kids.
Mosaic outside art play: I do not know what the story is behind this  coloured mosaic outside Art Play, but it is wonderful.
Textured path: The wng, textured pathway of cast iron acknowledges the significance of the eel as a tradil food source for groups camped by the river.
Watching rowers from Birrarung Marr: Sit on the seats under a shady tree watching rowers go by.
To Princes Bridge: The gravel path on the river bank is a bit quieter. More seats and looking back to Princess Bridge.
West along the river: From 'Angel' you can get a good look along the  River
Angel: Angel (ceramic, steel and concrete) by Dah Halpern is an artwork commissioned by the Nal Gallery of Victoria. It is even more impressive than the photo suggests.
hill for rolling: There should be more  hills like this one in the centre of cities. Watch the number of kids who are immately drawn to it and roll down laughing.
Walking up the slope to the bridge: The trees and shrubs set in the stone fence as you walk up the slope to the William k bridge.
William k bridge: A purpose built walking (and cycling) space, William k bridge is one of true des of . Beautiful and funcl.

Listening to Proximities: Proximities is a public art installation commissioned for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.  The stories and songs from 53 Commonwealth nations come out of the many, many srs across the bridge.
Sit and watch : Sit on the bridge and look south to the  and Tennis Centre or north to the  and listen to the trains go by under.
Off the bridge to the 'G': Coming off the bridge and walk to the MCG under the shade of magnificent old Elm trees.
The MCG: The MCG, what a collosseum. You 't realise how massive it is until you actually see it. Even if you 't like sport, the sound of the crowd cheering will grab your attention.
Dennis Lillee: Bronze statues do around the MCG, none more impressive than the great Dennis Lillee.
Aussie Rules: Statue commemorating the first game of ian Rules Football said to be played nearby on 7 August 1858.
Station: Its a beautiful the old train bridge. Catch a train (or tram) back to  St or keep going.
Watt's Cottage: Home to early settlers in Sorrento, this h was built in 1869. The Pioneer Memorial Garden is well tended with blooms all r round. Tours available (at limited times).
Information boards and cafe: Check out the information boards here for details about the history, local environment and features of the area. All S Cafe located a  walk away from here.
Surf's up: A good spot to watch the surf, have a picnic, go for a swim, read a book or do whatever you please.
Uphill climb tos the top: Definitely a steep climb uphill but the scenery from the top is very worthwhile. Get your heart rate up!
Panoramic views: A perfect spot to watch the , or simply enjoy the sweeping panoramic views.
Heading down to the beach: Follow the track, which will eventually take you tos the beach.
Fine : Enjoy the salty sea breezes as you feel the sand under your feet on this beautiful stretch of coastline.
Surf Lifesaving Club: You can take a detour here if you need a toilet stop.
'Lon Bridge': A great spot to explore pools and wander under the 'Lon Bridge' (but not ng high tide of course). You can continue along the beach all the way to Point Nepean if you like.
Public toilets and drinking : Phew! It's a pretty steep ramp that leads you up here. A convenient toilet stop and a chance to top up your water bottle before heading off again.

Start of 's Folly Track: There's a sign a near the car park marking the start of the track. Apparently Capt R  simply lit a match wherever he thought the bush needed to be cleared for the army\'s weapons training areas.
Looking out to the sea: Listen out for the twitter of small birds in this fabulous bit of coastal bushland overlooking the sea.

Unexploded bombs: A former weapons training area. "All large unexploded ordinance has been removed but you may come across small arms such as rifle and pistol shells," which of course, you shouldn't touch.

Point Nepean Visitor Centre: The visitor centre has plenty of local information and maps of the area. You can take a tour to the historical Fort Nepean (a buggy can transport you there). Public toilets and BBQ available here.

Mighty high fences: You can take a  detour down to the beach via Cove Ave. Clearly residents here like their pri but it's such a shame that the street is marred by these enormously high walls and fences.
Nature strip plantings: Thankfully, there are patches of wonderful plants to enjoy as you walk down the street.
A little bit arty: ... and even a bit of art to give some of these high walls a little bit of character.
On the other side: Across the road are a row of charming cottages that reminds us of how the area used to look before the high walls and fences came along.
Bus stop: You can catch bus number 788 back to Sorrento, or all the way back to  along point Nepean Road.
Boardwalk near fishing platforms: The boardwalks starts along the path just past the carpark on  Drive. A few fishing platforms go off the boardwalk.
Wetlands: The inlet is on one side of the boardwalk and wetlands on the other, both have an abundance of birdlife and aquatic life.
The shared path: The shared path is very popular with walkers and bike riders alike and is in pretty good cion.
Pelicans and piers: There are many little jetties dotted along the path and it is hard not to spot a pelican or two perched on many of them.
Raised boardwalks: The wonderful raised boardwalk provides a shady spot to look out to the inlet.
harbour: Old and new, big and small boats (but nothing too flash!) in the  harbour.
Coull's Inlet: Coull's Inlet is beautiful on a still early morning.
Fishing spot: One of the many fishing spots along the walk. Even if you are not into fishing, it's fun to watch early morning anglers.
Goat & other nds: Beautiful views abound on the walk. , Rabbit nd and more...
d boats: Over the summer, many camping ground visitors more theri boats along the shore. Boats for fishing, water skiing, bird watching or pleasure....
Foreshore Holiday Park: The next part of the walk goes through the council caravan park, in summer there is always something to look at.
To Capt. Sson's Point: If you want, you can take a  detour off the path and follow the water to Capt. Sson's Point (or stay on the path up above).
Capt. Sson's Point: A great spot to look up the inlet or to the mouth (and watch boats go out to sea). You can even see Gabo nd from here.
Koalas: If you look carefully you can often see Koalas in the trees, even the odd kan.
Cng the inlet: To get across to the beach you have to wade across about 20 meteres of the inlet which is about 45 cm p. In summer teh water is quite warm so it is very pleasant.
Dirftwood structure: This structure that some have built in the sand dune out of driftwood has been there for a while, hope it lasts a while longer!
beach: On a clear day the beach is beautiful other times it can be rugged and wild, but no less wonderful. This part is only for strong competent swimmers. But watch the surfers!
A walking beach: The beach is certainly great for walking, but can get a bit blowy.
Patrolled beach: This is the main swimming beach that is patrolled by life savers in the holiday season. Any one for cricket?
Bastion Point: Rockpools to look at and a good spot for snorkling off teh rocks when the cions are good.

Native flowers.: You'll come to a fork in the path. Walk this route as a loop or simply walk along the river till the end and return. Either way there is much to see. We found these feather like flowers. How lovely!
Beautiful views of the river: There are lots of birds enjoying the river. We saw several different types of birds swimming in the river.

Duck sanctuary: We saw a mother duck and her  ducklings nestled in a log along the river. A r nest away from predators and people. She's hard to spot in the photo because we didn't want to get too close!

Stray fruit bat: We spotted a stray fruit bat in one of the trees. It had clearly fallen behind from the group and was trying to remain hidden from prying eyes. We photographed it from afar so we wouldn't disturb it.
Still reflections: A lovely view from along the river.
Ducks and more birds: Many birds of all sorts can be found near the boat h because they're used to people feng them, even though feng birds is harmful (see link).
Barbeque areas: The bbq, tables and seats are under sheltered areas. There is plenty of idyllic picnic spots in shady areas close the river. Great spot for a picnic or gathering.
Signs: So many options! Take your pick.
Popular route: We passed several walkers, including children, a couple with a baby (must be a  4 wheeler pram!) and others using the route for exercise.
Skate Park : Large skate park ideal for families.
Jetty : A jetty to admire the scenic surrounds or do a spot of fishing.
BBQ facilities : Large undercover BBQ facilities.
Cafe by the lake : A cafe overlooking the lake.
Bridge: Walk across the bridge and take in the beautiful surroundings.
Canoe Club: Canoe hire available from Visitor Information Centre.Canoes can accomodate 2 adults. Kayaks also available.
Aquamoves: Aquamoves is an aquatic and leisure centre with facilities such as gym, creche sauna, indoor and outdoor pools.
All Abilities Playground: A playground suitable for children and families of all abilities.
Aquamoves: Aquamoves is an aquatic and leisure centre with gym and areboic facilities, creche, indoor and outdoor pools.
Playground: There is a playground for the children to play on. So the whole family can come to the lake and enjoy the scenery.
Fitness Station: Fitness equipment to help you in your work out.
dogs off leash area: Area where you can let your dog off the lead. It also has a creek.
Bird Watching: You can spy on many different varieties of birds in the wetlands.
Fishing: One of the many good places to fish at the lake.
Boat Ramp: A place to put your small boat.
The beach: One of the beaches to relax on or walk along.
Cashins Mill: Built in the early 1850s by  Kneen of Fitzroy. After James Cashin Snr died in 1873, the mill was operated by sons James and William.
Farmers Market: First Sunday of the month - 8am to 1pm.  Park (next to Lilly Lake), sea Road, Lily.
Rivers: Be alert for high river levels and fast flowing water which can make the Gorge hazardous.The best walking period lasts from early November until late .
Variety of views: The scenic walks take in a range of landscapes.
Falls: There are three s along the track.
ian  Walk: Features all ian plants, including sky-high trees and land-dwelling shrubs.
Eucalypts : A collection of over 200 eucalypts; ia's most iconic trees.
Lions Head and Setion Trees: These trees are remnants of the River Red Gum and pre-date European settlement.
Lower  River Habitat: An ecological collection which contains genous plants native to the Lower  region.
Long nd: A garden which is representative of vegetation pre-European settlement and contains many genous plant species.
Sidney Myer Music Bowl: Attend the free Wellbeing music concert at the Bowl at 12pm after the walk to celebrate the wellbeing of Aboriginal and er people.
Smoking Ceremony: Experience a tradil genous Smoking Ceremony in the midst of the ancestral lands of  nation (allocated times).
General Store:  shop offers drinks, food, papers, a postal service, liquor and petrol. Workers from nearby businesses often drop in and the locals catch up for a chat.
Tennis Courts:  has teams in the local Tennis competition in both Juniors and s.  Junior "Slam and Sweat" tennis sessions are also conducted here along with midweek competitions.
Recreation Reserve: Includes the   which is used for a variety of groups such as Playgroup, Exercise classes and the Womens circus.  The  Market is held here the first Saturday of the month.
Black Saturday Monument: A monument recognising the Remlaw fire that went through  and cuased much damage in February 2009
Primary School: Set partly back from the road, this school provides education for a little under 100 students.  The small numbers and intimate setting is appealing to many.

Tasma Terrace - 2-12 Parliament Place: The terrace is quarters of the Nal Trust. It comprised important bo hs from the 1870s. Managing a bo h was one of the few employment options available to early women.

the Great Petition sculpture - Burston Reserve : This artwork represents a giant petition with 30,000 signatures offered to the Victorian Parliament in 1891 as evidence of widespread support for equal voting rights for women.
Chisholm Cairn - Burston Reserve: Commemorates the centenary of the death of philanthropist  Chisholm, who served the community by welcoming immis and building shelters for travellers to the  at .
Women\'s Underground Toilet - Gor Reserve, near Spring St: The toilet is one of 11 erected by the  of  between 1902 and 1939. The group is now unique in ia.

Parliament H - Spring St: Victoria was last to  women suffrage in 1908.A plaque in the garden honours Vida Goldstein,pioneer suffragist and first woman in the British Empire to stand for election to a nal parliament.

Windsor Hotel - 111 Spring St: Sitting over the main entrance are 2 classically inspired figures draped in s. The female statue on the right represents Peace, while the male figure on the left represents Plenty.
The Lyceum Club - 9  Place: The Lyceum, the famous professl women's club was a purpose-built place, created by and for women, in Victoria.
Chs - 9  St: This building was erected specifically as artists' studios. Amongst other women who had a studio here, Jane Sutherland was regarded as the leading woman artist of the  School.
WCTU Rooms - 15  St: The Women's Christian rance Union was the largest and most infntial of the various women's organisations in Victoria in the late 1890s.

The  Club - 36  St: Established in 1838, the  Club is Victoria's oldest institution. Women are excluded from membership of this bastion of conservatism and one of the most exclusive organisations in Victoria.

Harley H - corner of  & Exhibition St: The Nal Council of Women, based here for 2 decades effectively lobbied for legtion and representation on all boards and committees relating women and children's welfare and legal rights.

Alexandra Club - next to Harley H: Founded in 1903, this is one of ia's longest established and exclusive clubs for women. Members include Dame Elisabeth , community worker and women's rights activist  Beaurepaire.
Le Louvre - 74  St: Formerly a boutique by Lillian man promoting high fashion European designers. The boutique played a role in establishing  as the fashion capital of ia that it has become today.

Nauru H - 80  St : The ian Conciliation and Arbitration Commission was located here from 1979 - 2006, and women campaigners for equal pay re-enacted the 1969 chain up detration at the site on 31 October 1985.

St Michael's Uniting Church - corner  &  St: Women have been part of the congregation since its opening in 1867. The Uniting Church has allowed female ministers who serve in parishes, and some females have been Moderators.
Lane: Thousands of women worked in the rag trade and endured poor working cions such as long hours and low wages. Few buildings of the textile and clothing industries remain. Rosati's is one of them.
Former women's buildings -  St: The  meeting place for many women's reformist groups. WCTU's first headquarters at 28  St was where girls from nearby workrooms could get cheap good meals.

Scots Church - corner  and  St: Dame Nellie  sang in the church choir as a child. When she died, the funeral service was held here. Women have been members of the congregation since 1874 but cannot serve as ministers.

Assembly  - next to Scots Church - 156 -160  St: Used for the Women\'s Parliament, which was conducted on parliamentary lines with a ministry and political parties and provided useful training in public speaking and parliamentary procedure.

Theosophical Society - 181  St: Once home to the Theosophical Society. Many women have been members of the society, and have been elected president over the rs. The current Theosophical Society building is at 126-28  St.
The Atheneaum - 188  St: The talented artist Clarice Beckett had large rly exhibitions at the Athenaeum from 1924 until 1932. The building\'s facade contains a statue of , patron goddess of wisdom.

Former underground women's toilet - corner ll  St: Built in 1902, this was the first such toilet built as a result of the lobbying by many women, including members of the Womens Political and Social Crusade. It is now under the sculpture at the site.
Chinatown - Little  St: An early centre for prostitution and poverty, the Stion Army established a  in Little  Street to do battle for the souls of prostitutes and larrikins in the 19th century.

Queen Victoria Hospital - 210  St: One of only 3 hospitals in the world to be founded, managed and staffed by women. It was ia\'s first female mcal service, established by ia\'s first female doctor in 1896.

State Library - 328 ston St: Helen Garner wrote her well-known novel 'Monkey Grip' at the library. In the forecourt is the statue of Joan of Arc, the nal 15th century heroine of France and saint of the n Cic Church.

Storey  - 344-46 ston St: Various women's organisations rented the premises, including the Women's Peace Army associated with Vida Goldstein. Purple and green are colours of the Irish and early feminists who once occupied it.
Women's Liion Office - 16 Little La T St: Feminists from the Women's Liion Movement Centre produced a newspaper Vashti's Voice, which promoted women's rights such as equal pay and abortion.

Welsh Church - 320 La T St: The first free dispensary for women in 1896 was set up here. In the first 3 months the clinic treated 2,000 women and children. This led to the establishment of the Queen Victoria Hospital.

YWCA's Jasper Hotel - 489  St: Established in 1882, the organisation provides housing services, job placement and mentoring for many women. Inside is a plaque acknowledging  Henry, pioneer journalist and unionist.

Emily McPherson College (now RMIT) - 379-405  St: Established to improve the domestic skills of women at a time when there was a push for 'scientific' mothering education, also when a  woman's access to secondary education was limited.
Old  Gaol - 377  St: Ned 's mother, Ellen, was a prisoner in the women's cell b when Ned was hanged in 1880. She was in trouble for aiding and abetting Ned and charged with attempted murder.

Watch H - next to the former Magistrates Court: The first prisoner here was  s, who was charged with indecent language. The Nal Council of Women and WCTU fully lobbied to improve some cions for female prisoners.

Magistrates Court - corner La T and  St: Jennie  was sentenced to 6 months' jail for repeated violations of the War Precautions Act in 1919 for flying red flags. She went on a hunger strike and was released after 4 days.

Green Latrine - corner Spring and LaT St: On 21 October 1969 Zelda D'Aprano, a feminist crusader chained herself to the Commonwealth Building (known as the 'Green Latrine', now demolished) until she was cut free by the Commonwealth police.

Princess Theatre - 163 Spring St: Many famous actresses have performed at the theatre, including Nellie Stewart, Sibyl Tdike, Marlene Dietrich and Marina Prior. Nellie Stewart, who starred in the first performance of 'The Mikado'.
Visitor centre and restaurant: We start the walk from the visitors centre that overlooks Jells lake.  The restaurant is open every day except Christmas Day.
Wattles in bloom: As soon as you start  down to the lake you will notice some wonderful native flora to your right.
Pacific Black Duck: Around the lake there is abundant bird life including the versatile Pacific Black Duck. It frequents all types of water and is found in all but the most arid regions of ia.
Eurasian Coot: The Eurasian Coot is easy to find.  Its an omnivore, and will take a variety of small live prey including the eggs of other water birds, as well as algae, vegetation, seeds and fruit.
A stroll in the park: The path s along the edge of open parkland before heading into the conservation area.
By ide: When you are near the lake listen out for some of the thousands of frogs that live here.  They do not drink water, and instead absorb it through their skin.
Chestnut Teal: When you are cng the creek you might spot a Chestnut Teal looking for lunch.   A male teal is pictured here agitating the sow water ..
Chestnut Teal Upended: .. before upending to bottom feed underwater.

Wetlands: The wetlands act as filters, sponges and reserves of water.  Though only 2% of Victoria is wetland area, it supports 33% of our endangered plants and is home to mammals, frogs, fish and insects.
Nesting Boxes: Hollows in old trees are home to many native birds.  As there are not enough hollows for all the native species that utilise the nesting boxes dotted around the park.
The conservation area: The conservation area immerses you in native flora, while you are serenaded by the varied songs of the birdlife it supports.

Bird Hide: The bird hide provides a great opportunity to watch the birdlife.  The hide has an information board with pictures and descriptions of some of the birdlife you may see.  Bring your binoculars!

Purple Swamphen: The park is home to a sizeable population of the beautiful Purple Swamphen.  The male has an elaborate courtship display, holding water weeds in his bill and bowing to the female with loud chuckles!
Enjoy the scenery of the park: Can you hear the peace and quiet? This stretch is great for spotting birds and listening to their songs.
Civic Park:  Civic Park is set in a small valley, with a pond, , rotunda, playground and public toilets. The park also includes the 'Path of Achievement'.

Wetlands: Wetlands have been established through this part of the walk and the  Landcare Group have planted hundreds of native trees to increase biodiversity and improve water quality and amenity.

s Track Cenotaph: Here a memorial is located in recognition to William , the first Chairman of Country Roads Board, for his outstanding contribution to Victorias road network.

genous history: A number of interpretive signs explain the local genous history, creation stories and artwork of the Gunaikurnai, one of the Aboriginal nations of ia.

area: Stop here for a rest or a picnic and perhaps spot an Eastern  Kans or Black Wallaby if you are here early or at dusk.

Spurling H, 38 Black St (1888): The Spurling H is the only known  design by  based architect John Horbury Hunt, who was a figure of controversy in his time due to his innovative and daring new designs.
7 Bleazby Ave (2005). John Tallis: The philosophy behind the corrugated iron is that it wraps the inside spaces, as if protecting the family, with the timber-clad forms inside this metal skin.
Heaz, 66  Street (1891): Built as a residence for 's Health , Cornelius  M.D., Heaz was one of many Victorian era hs in the  area to adopt elements of the Queen Anne style.
26  St,  (1878): rt , a ful miner from the  , built the first stage of this h, then became bankrupt the next r.
166-168 Church St (1890): Rrumoured to be built for two sisters, there are only a few two-storey semi-detached residences in  and these are  a sophisticated example of the Inate style.

161 Church St (1885): Built by ful  stationer Alfred  as a family residence, the h features a tower with
a 'widow's walk' (the topmost lookout).

167 Church St (1886): Calabria's asymmetrical facade is emphasised by a two- storey cast-iron veah containing Gothic motifs in its lacework. From 1900-07, Emma A'Beckett (1838-1906) lived in this g h.

76-90 Church St (1888-89): 's Buildings consist of seven two-storey rendered brick shops, with a central laneway.  The original shop fronts have all been altered, but the facades of the upper level remain intact.
71-73 Church St (1912): \'s former post office uses bold chtic brickwork; the distinctive stucco and brick porch is unusual, with its strong position on the corner.

Former Congregal Church, 17 Black St (1875): The former Congregal Church is a superb example of an Early English-inspired Gothic church expressed in bichtic brick. Designed by Charles  and built by James Bonham.
58 Carpenter St (pre 1859): The first  rate books are dated 1859, and no. 58 was already firmly established as a h and brewery. It is one of the few hs remaining that pre-date the rate books.
37 Black St: W, one of 's stunning villas, features a wealth of decorative detail, a return veah, and projecting bay windows on two sides.

corner: This aqueduct was created by horse power in the 1930s to feed nearby  reservoir. This gully is one of the more moist spots upon this level, easy section of this walk

where aqueducts meet: This siphon marks the point where a second aqueduct from a spring in s to the north fed into the main aqueduct. We can't follow the aqueduct here, but pick it up a little further on
The upper aqueduct: The northern aqueduct is more overgrown, but the west embankment provides a reasonably clear course for the  distance of 250 metres. There are fine views to the north and west
Shire  quarry: This disused quarry only operated from 1913 to 1917, and provided  Shire Council with road metal via a narrow gauge 3 km horse-drawn tramway thru the Police Paddocks to Stud Road

crest of the range: The actual summit is sly north of the track on private property, but even from the fence line there are excellent views in the direction of the , and also wildlife in the mornings and evening

stonemasons track: The name of this track is literal. Beside the trail can be seen evidence of small scale quarrying, and the brick remains of buildings where the stonemasons lived and worked more than 100 rs ago
flagpole: This rusty flagpole is a link to ia's darkest hour. In 1941, a military camp was hurriedly set up here to stop a Japanese invasion of . Its commander, Col. George , had it moved

Back on the aqueduct: This is the  of the main aqueduct we picked up 5 km earlier. The flat walking trail is an easy return route to the main picnic area, though there is much traffic noise from the nearby road

Arboretum entrance: This is another good spot from which to access this walk. And note, there are free "poop bags"available to assist in cleaning up after your dog.
Bridge across the : Find this bridge to cross the  and return via the north side of the river. It is easy to find and well marked from the walking path.
Back Germantown Rd back to the walking path: Continue along the road until you see the river path access again. Easy to find.

There are lots of seats along the way: There are many nice spots to rest those weary legs.

So many birds of all shapes and sizes: If you stop and look up you will be amazed just how many birds there are to see!

Welcome to the Community Greenh Corridor : The walk starts right next to the Princes Highway, or it can be an extension of the Toomuc Creek Trail existing south of the highway.
The path is a mix of grass, concrete and gravel: The path is a mix of grass, concrete and gravel. The first half of the walk is a concrete path and well suited to prams and wheelchairs.
Careful cng the side strees: There are a number of side streets that need to be crossed, make sure you look both ways!
Tick Bush: First stop. Look for the tick bush, an  shrub. Its flowers usually  appear from September to December. Did they flower earlier? Check it out
Flannel Flower: Out of the track, you will have the chance to observe the Actinotus Helianthi. 't forget to upload the pictures you take on the CteWatch app.
Lily: Continuing on the path, you are going to see  a giant tussock-like, rosette plant.  They can reach 5m high with the flower stalk.!
White Cedar: The White Cedar is one of only a few native ian plants that are seasonally deciduous, although many species drop their leaves ng droughts.
Fuchsia Heath: Fuchsia Heath's flowers are long and tubular, some of them have pink-red tubed and white lobes, others are white. Spot them!
Red Spider Flower: You might ask what is this? It's not a spider. It is a bright red, occaslly pink flower. Its spider appearance  explains its name. Keep recording for CteWatch app!
Frogs: Listen for frogs. The link below will help you to recognize them and to catalouge them. Have fun!
: This giant tree is just past the cafe. s aren't related to other oak trees at all but are actually a species of Grevilla and are very popular with birds!
Firewheel Tree: This beautiful native tree on your righ has striking red flowers. Are they out today?

brook Community Hub: This state of the art Hub features a new library, community centre and spaces, community health services, maternal and child health services, early rs centre, Men's Shed and  optometry services.
brook Park: brook Park offers the community a peaceful place to walk and take in some fresh air.  Take friends and family, kick the footy or enjoy a picnic on the grass.

Paul Sadler Swimland brook: Paul Sadler Swimland has received many as in ia and USA, including the induction of Paul Sadler into the ian Swim Coaches and Teachers' Association  of Fame. Call while it's hot!

Kinder Smith Playground: Kinder Smith Reserve has been given a face lift, with a new concrete walking path around the oval, and fresh landscaping. The local  children will love this exciting new playground!

Owned by the   Council and managed by YMCA Victoria, RecWest offers sport-based activities and programs for all.

GreenWORKS! Mural: The GreenWORKS! project, a ful council and community collaboration, provides a strong connection between the built environment, the natural world and the place the brook locals call home.

Kinder Smith Reserve: Are you a team player? Kinder Smith Reserve is home to Sunshine Football Club, Sunshine YCW Cricket Club and RecWest brook. Contact RecWest for enquiries about netball, basketball or futsal.
B  Vietnamese Restaurant and Cafe: Try a selection of delicious dishes from the menu and discover the tropical dise out the back. You will want to go back for more!
Regulations: The Conglomerate Gully Flora Reserve has its own set of legtive regulations!  They ar eposted on a sign near the start of the walk.
Information board: An information board near the start of the walk gives a summary of the history, ecology and geology of the reserve.
Hollo: This hollo stands by the side of the path.  Great for hide and seek.
Fallen log: In a number of places, particularly this part of the walk, large fallen logs or trees are a feature.  They make good seats for adults and excellent play equipment for children!
Hut: This interesting hut provides shelter - and curiosity.
Lookout: The track starts to climb alongside a small gorge, with a stream flowing through it after rain or at wetter times of the r.  A lookout provides this view down the gorge.
Climbing: The climb starts to get steep in this area, but that only adds to the sense of accomplishment.  Keep an eye on any under 5s though.
A taste of NT: At times the landscape in this area is reminiscent of the northern territory, with woodland on y escarpment.
Cascades: The stream falls down the gorge, with a series of small s after rain.  The wetter it has been, the better they are. Unfortunately, was dry at the time of our visit.
Pools: Even at the driest times, small pools remain in the streambed.  They appear to harbour life, but I'm not an entymologist.
Clearing: At the highest point in the walk, you reach a clearing next to the stream above one of the s.

Burnt tree: Old burnt trees and stumps are a reminder that this area has high risk of bushfire.  In the summer, check the fire risk for the day before visiting.  Do not come on a day of total fire ban.
Rocks and lichen: In this area particularly, rocks with coloured lichen will re those who look carefully.
It's only grass: Native grass dominates at ground level in Conglomerate Gully.
Waves of grass: At times the native grass seems to be rolling down  in waves.
Native : The interplay of native trees, grass and fallen logs is perhaps the defining feature of this walk.
Wildlife: Wildlife on this walk is not used to humans and will typically move away from you - g it difficult to photograph!  Thanks to digital enhancement, you can make out this wong.

Water Tower: The Water Tower is one of a few peppered around the district. Built in 1957, the tower provides water pressure for thousands of homes across the urban area and has the capa to store 2.7 megalitres

158  Avenue: The building is now the Guide , but originally was home to the Seventh Day Adventists, and  following that the Lutheran Church. The Church outgrew the site in 1966 when two congregations merged.

“Valetta” 223 Eleventh St: Built 1891 and believed to be designed by D.T. Edmunds who supervised construction of Rio .  Valetta is on the corner of  Place and two pillars at its entrance mark the little street.
Primary Schoo: Opened on September 13, 1890 with 300 eager students, despite the building not yet being complete. A r later, once all works were finished,  Primary was official opened.
Proudfoot H: Built 1891 for John Proudfoot who owned a produce store in . This fine example of a late Victorian brick h was later the Presbyterian Manse for many rs, before moving into private hands.
Avenue: There are still a number of attractive homes in this street but sadly many have been lost.

Lemon Avenue : Few streets in  have retained their identity as well as Lemon Ave. This area was the tradesmen’s class and 3 of the hs along Lemon Avenue predate 1900 and another 14 are pre World War I
50 Lemon Ave: A good example of the simple Edian Style. Currently a backpackers’ hostel, but its original owner was A.C Pugsley, who commissioned the home in 1902.

Kathleen  Kindergarten: Originally started down by the river, Kathleen  Kindergarten was founded by 
Kathleen   (a member of the Bowring family) as a free kindergarten for children.

Settlers Club: The ‘Setts’ as it’s commonly referred to, has been on this site since 1893. A prominent club until 1993, the 'Setts' is now  a modern office space,  popular bar, restaurant and function centre .
77  Avenue: Original Methodist Parsonage and was designed by William Sheridan and built in 1892. It’s an unusual example of a Tudoresque Victorian brick villa.
: A little after the start of the track is some beautifully gnarled s that make the path look like a bit like a .

Home to endangered species: Coo Woodland is home to a number of threatened and endangered species; the swift parrot, -headed flying  and growling grass frog have all been spotted here.
cut: There's a path along the back fences of hs that's good for bikes and  cuts. It takes you from the Serpentine Road entrance to the Coo Reserve sports ovals.

Spreading Wattle: This wattle has needle leaves. Its lemon-cream globular flower-heads brighten the  ng the Spring season.
Bracken: It is easy to find  Bracken which can out-compete other plants to form a dense understorey. It creates a humid microcte under its leaves and is food for a variety of native insects.
Local housing development: This bird box has a f small hole which would suit the White-throated Treecreeper, the Red-browed Treecreeper, the Feathertail Glider and the Sugar Glider amongst others.
Common  : Keep an eye out for interesting shrubs along the route.    is a slender shrub, native to ia. The upper leaves are narrow and long while the lower leaves are oval-shaped.

Look up: It is worth stopping to appreciate the wonderful canopy overhead and the endless shades of green on show.  It is also a good opportunity to spot some of the 88 local species of birdlife darting about.
Abundant flora: 336 species of genous plants have been recorded in the Reserve.  Every visit to the reserve is reed by new discoveries!
Bushy Needlewood: The prickly foliage of these understorey plants provides safe nesting sites for small birds and also provides nectar for native bees.
Walking among the trees: Trees along the walk include Stringybark and  the 60m high Mountain  gums
Park: Home of the Brunswick Zebras and general community play area. Often see many dogs running around here too.
Bridge across to Merri Park: You could take a quick detour over the bridge, there is a children's playground.
Kirk Street Park : Features a recently upgraded children's playground (people have left toys to share in the sandpit!) and replanted, landscaped area.

Bench at path to .: If you 't been, a visit to CERES Community Environmental Park is definitely worth the detour (has food and drinks too).
The path: The path drops down close the Creek.
Russian Orthodox Church: A magnificent looking building, particularly when the sun shines on the spires.
Brunswick velo: The velo has recently been improved and it is open to the public so you can see all sorts of people riding around. It is also the home of the Brunswick Cycling Club.
One of many seats: A welcome seat on a warm day (there are other seats along the path)
Shady path: A nice stretch of shady path.
H Street Bridge: Great example of a suspension bridge. Cyclists are supposed to walk their bikes, like this respectful  chap, but be d some 't and it's very narrow.
Farmgate: Merri Creek Market Garden : 't know anything about this urban farm but, it always good to look at what is being grown.
Retaining wall: The  retaining wall is quite beautiful, it's bit like a sculpture.

Red-necked Stints: These small birds migrate from the northern hemisphere where they breed, to Victoria in summer.  They arrive in August and depart in February-.
High-tide detour: If the tide is in, you can walk along a wide path behind the beach, dotted with old pine trees.  It curves around Point  to the white .

The Tower: There are great views from the tower platform.  Artist Bill  designed it as A Monument to Migration and Astions - using the theme of bird migration as a symbol for human migration.
The Wetlands: The wetlands are a migratory  for birds, some from as far away as Siberia and Japan.  The area is home to more than 200 species of birds including rare and endangered species.
Saltmarsh flora: If you look closely there are lots of  plants who find this cenging environment quite suitable for their needs including the Rounded Moon-flower and Beaded Glasswort.

1. Site of 's old market (/Market//Mair b): This has long been a public and central meeting place - situated at  of roads, and a few minutes from rail transport and 's key cultural and civic institutions.

2. The Civic , 300 Mair St,  built 1953-1956: Multi-purpose venue, with monumental presence.   Steel frame, local Selkirks bricks.  Main  holds c. 1600,  Performers included INXS.  Closed 2002, reopened 2014 for community design process.

3. Statue of play William Shakespeare by r Meszaros, by 300 Mair St: Statue added to front of  1960 depicts Shakespeare receiving applause after a performance.   Hungarian visitor Karoly Nagy was so impressed he organised a replica for Budapest unveiled 2003.

4. Ginkgo trees planted by Sir Paul & Lady Hasluck 1972, western end  skate park: Planted ng Vice-regal visit, the trees are of the ancient Ginkgo biloba species (Maidenhair tree), native to China, called living fossils as sir to fossils dating back 270 million rs.

5. Statue of Scottish writer Sir Walter Scott by Stanley , by 300 Mair St: The centenary of gold celebrations in the early 1950s gave a renewed push to plans for a new Civic  so it is fitting that both the Scott & Shakespeare statues record links to Goldrush times.

6. Lower  entrance,  St : The architects of the  made r use of the fall of the ground on the site from West to East to build the foyer of the Lower  under the stage of the Main .  Note messages on doors.

7. View of fly tower,  St : The tall tower like structure at the northern end of the  is the Fly Tower. This is the part of the building designed to store and launch the sets for large scale theatrical productions.

8.  Library upper story offices, Market St : The relationship with the Civic  was considered ng the design of the  Library built 1993-1994,  The  upper story offices echoes the brickwork of the Civic .

9. Mural, Civic /Library Car Park, off Market St: A colourful public art mural has been created on the back wall of the carpark.   The mural was painted in 2013 by local youth working alongside professl artist Pauline O'Shannessy-Dowling.
10. View to railway precinct, cnr Market &  St: The proximity to the Provincial Hotel and Railway Station beyond it is evident from this corner of the site.

11. Skate park,  St : The skate park was the initiative of a   skater and was added to the site in the 1990s.  A replacement skate park was built at the Len T  reserve in 2004 but this remains popular.

12. Regent Cinema, 49 Lydiard St Nth : The cinema's interior was rebuilt in 1943 to the design of , Murphy & Appleford after a major fire attrid to visiting Amn service personnel.    Murphy was later co-architect Civic .

13. Mair to Sturt B, Lydiard St Nth,  : This b is now one of the most treasured in  encompassing Victorian era architectural gems.  However records show that in the 1940s this was one site proposed for a new civic .

14. Site of Alfred , Cnr Curtis &  Sts, demolished 1956: Site of a predecessor of the Civic , constructed n 1867 on the boundaries of East & West  for 's first royal visitor and formally closed on the day the Civic  opened.

15. Former Walter Davis store, 86 Bridge Mall : An example of the commercial work of Civic  architect Les  who remodelled the store in 1935 with distinctive art deco features.   was known for both his commercial & residential work.

16. Site of Coliseum, Little Bridge Street (vicinity   Citizen's Centre): Another very large  (capa up to 10,000) owned by the South Street Society and used for society & civic events. It burnt down in 1936 creating impetus for the building of a new public .

17. Her Majesty's Theatre ('Her Maj'),17 Lydiard St South : Historic theatre first opened in 1875.   The history of the Civic  intersected with that of 'Her Maj' from 1990 - 2002 as the  of  combined management of the two facilities.

18.  Town , 225 Sturt St : The eventual design of the Civic  was innovative in seting  facilities and the Council admin offices.  Architect Les  was greatly interested in civic matters as long-time Councillor.
19. B Arcade, 321 Sturt St : The Sturt Street entrance of the B Arcade was remodelled by Les  in 1937. Look up to the first floor to get the best view of this work, the stylised pet and lettering.

20. State Government Offices, Cnr Mair &  Streets : To the west of the Civic  is another public building - the State Government Offices opened in 1981 and known as "The Glass H" because of its distinctive glass curtain wall design.
Start of walk: Underwood Park sign with large map of main attractions - lots of free parking.

g gazebo: g gazebo with landscaped surrounds.

Path over duck pond: This part of the path goes over the duck pond through the trees. There are lots of ducks, but you may have to look a little harder to find the large  fish and the turtles.
Playground: A shady playground for the kids - right next to tables, seats, toilets and some of the sporting s (e.g. netball, softball). The caretaker's hut is also close by.
Dog park: Two fenced dog parks with multiple access points. One is for smaller dogs and one is for larger dogs. Both parks have water, plastic doggy bags, bins and seats.
Daisy Painting: All of the telephone poles have been painted with beautiful ian scenes.
Building mural: What a great mural! A few of the buildings in this area have been painted to blend into the scenery.
Picnic tables, BBQ and toilets: This is a very popular picnic spot in summer. There are gas BBQs, several picnic tables and benches, and toilets. Photo by Parks Victoria.
Start of walking track: We took Coerrk Track, a vehicle track that follows . Alternate routes include Lyrebird Track and Slip Creek Track. They're roughly the same distance but have steps.
Fresh mountain air: Fill your lungs with the fresh air from the surrounding . The sun dappled  made our walk truly magical!
Tree canopy: 't forget to look up every now and then as you might spot some local birds or simply to enjoy the view.
Popular walk, even in the middle of winter: This walk is popular in summer as a lovely way to cool off, and in winter to enjoy the crisp and refreshing fresh air.
Colourful tree bark: The colours of a  are always a treat. The lush green ferns and the dew drops on them are gorgeous, while the colours of the barks of trees are varied and ever changing.
Get up close : s are the perfect subject if you like photography. There's no age of beautiful landscapes and interesting close-ups to snap.
: It's a treat to see the Creek after a rainy day as it's full and fast flowing.
Dam wall & spillway: The dam wall was constructed in 1927, and raised in 1936. Stone came from the crest of the range via horse-drawn tramway. The east shore is a popular picnic nd recreation area
Lake track: This section of track adjoins a flora & fauna conservation area, where local wildlife such as kans may be sighted, especially in the mornings and evenings
Mahogany track: The track is climbing, and there are farm ruins on the , not connected with those at the boy's farm. Thompson track is narrow and wng, with many tree roots
Boy's farm: The former boy's farm is sly off the main trail, with nume ruins and the former orchard now growing untended. The boy's farm closed more than 60 rs ago, yet much is still visible
Highest point: This is  on this trip, the knoll to the right around 100m ASL. The descent on Lyster track is steep and rocky, but only for a  distance
elan's farm : The elan family settled here in the 1930s, but only lived here a  time. Nume exotic trees still grow here, and the farm dam is clear to see
tramway: The walk joins the former  tramway at this point for a long, gentle descent to the west side of the dam wall. This track is for walkers only
Lake view: This point on the former tramway is one of the best view points of the lake on the west side. There is still something to see before rejoining the main path
Tramway display: This static display shows the type of stone hopper used on the narrow gauge horse-drawn  tramway. The hopper was manufactured in Leeds UK
Crayfish Bay signpost: Crayfish Bay signpost, all you need do is decide which track to take first. I reckon, take the beach way and cliff top back there is best.
The grottos: There a few grottos or small caves at the end of the first beach. Many a time on a rainy, cold winters day they have provided shelter.
h: The white spot in the cliff edge in the distance (middle of the photo) is the Cape Oyway h.
Rockpools: At low tide there are many, many rockpools to keep  and old fascinated.
Arriving at Cray Bay: Arriving at Cray Bay at low tide, on a still warm April morning. Beautiful.
Crayfish Bay: Crafish Bay at its best, on a very low tide, which is great for a snorkle ('t bother diving if it is not low tide).
Cray Bay and Otway Reef: Climbing up the track and looking down on Cray Bay and out to the Otway Reef
The Southern Ocean: A great spot to look out to the Southern Ocean and watch the rollers coming in.
The Cliff Top Track: The Cliff Top Track is very narrow and sometimes a little overgrown, but a de nonetheless.
The Boardwalk: A ish boardwalk.
Kensington Neighbourhood H: Providing a variety of programs for locals. Kensington Neighbourhood H has been running for 40 rs to help locals.
Women's Peace Garden: The Garden was conceived in 1986 as a part of the Internal r of Peace. Features plants symbolic of peace and colours of women's movement. It's a very relaxing place.
'The Back Gate' Mosaic Murals: Under the Epsom Road Bridge. Installed in 1998. Commemorates historic  yards. Animals passed the 'Back Gate' to leave the yards tos the abattoir or meatworks.
Kensington : Kensington is a nice place for walking around and there are many children’s playgrounds. It's a lovely place to live because public transport is very convenient.
Community Garden: If you're interested in renting a plot to grow your own vegetables, please contact Kensington Community Recreation Centre on 9376 1633 or kensington@ymca.org.au.
Wildlife: Apart from birds, sometimes you can see local wildlife on apartment balconies too.
River and Wetlands: You can walk or cycle along the river to visit the wetlands, or travel to other places from here.
Starfish: When the water is low you can see starfish on the river .
Road Park: This playground is great for children of all ages. The park also has BBQ, tables , seats and a water tap.
Victorian hs: Built ng the reign of Queen Victoria. Many hs have been lovingly restored.
The Kiln: When petrol rationing was introduced in 1940, charcoal was seen as a practical alternative.  This kiln is a rare example of a relatively intact charcoal burning kiln.
Friends of Kurth Kiln: The Friends are actively engaged in maintaining the notice board, the kiln site and the tracks on this walk.

Brown Stringy-bark trees: This versatile tree provided food, mcines, containers, string and
tools for Aboriginal people.
The creek: There are several great views of the creek along the walk.  Close your eyes and listen to the water running down stream.   What other sounds can you hear?
Common Heath: The heath flowers, which mainly occur between late autumn and early spring are white, pink or red in colour.  See if you can find a pink one, it is Victorias floral emblem.

Foam build-up: You can be forgiven for thinking it is a sign of pollution.  The foam is produced by the decomposition of a wide variety of plant material including aquatic plants and the leaves of trees.
End of  Creek track: The track returns to  Road on the opposite side of the bridge to where we started.
Picnic Area: After walking along the  track, this is a great spot to relax and listen to the birds singing.   You may hear lyrebirds, honeters, parrots and kookaburras.
Closer to nature: The path narrows at times immersing you in the sights and smells of ferns, bushes and trees along the way.
Tree down: A fallen tree has provided the opportunity for smaller plants to flourish.  Be the tree canopy you can find Silver Wattle, Spike Wattle, Christmas Bush, Silver  and tree ferns.

Hakea: Look out for Hakea along the route.  The nectar is used by insects and birds when it is in flower. Hakea requires fire to reproduce as the hard nut needs to be broken for the seed to be released.
Toilet on route: This toilet might provide welcome relief along the way.  It is only a s detour from the walking route.
The road home: The last section of the walk is a wide gravel road leading back to the kiln.

The Heritage Peppercorn Tree: South Amn Peppercorn trees were often planted near s in the colonial period. The White and Clements families ran the dairy farm Flora Vale in this area from the 1840s to the early 1970s.
The Relocated Scarred Tree: Scars on living trees are from Aboriginal people deliely removing bark or wood.
The Possum Tree: rs ago, major limb loss, fire and decay in this ancient river redgum (Eucalyptus camaldulensis) created a large opening with s and crannies for possums and birds to shelter.
possum: Look out for some local wildlife using the habitat these tress and understory provide.
Lakeview: Wetlands are home to aquatic and semi-aquatic genous plant species, water birds, frogs, fish and invertebrates. Wetlands were a major source of food, fibre and mcines for Aboriginal people.
The Fused-limb Tree: This can happen naturally but Aboriginal people also made it happen by deliely manipulating a growing tree. Either way, the trees are thought to have special significance.
Funky RMIT architecture: Enjoy the views of the funky built form.  Kids love this walk too!

Burls: A number of bulbous woody growths occur at the base of the trunk, called lignotubers or 'burls'.The Wurundjeri people sometimes removed the burls and crafted them into water containers called tarnuks.
Triple Scar and Redgum  Woodlands: Some of these redgums are well over 400 rs old. Help the Friends of the Bundoora Redgums restore the  understory to boost biodiversity.
The 'Canoe' Tree: The scar on this tree is probably from bark being deliely removed to make roofing material or a small food-collection canoe.
The Staircase: This non genous lemon scented gum  still provides nectar for the local possums as seen by the claw marks in its trunk.
The Resource Tree: Trees were major food sources for the Wurundjeri people. Birds, eggs, honey and possums could all be harvested from trees. This one has an access hole.
The Rectangular Cultural Scar: This is a highly significant tree. The scars size suggests the bark was used to build a shelter.

Frogpond: 6 species of frogs have been recorded in Bundoora, most of which need the wetlands to survive. Frogs have been around for 190 million rs and are an accurate cator of environmental wellbeing.
Woodland View and Re-vegetation site: The Friends of the Bundoora Redgums Inc, a volunteer organisation, has begun the long process of restoring the Redgum  Woodland to its former glory. Join in!

shops: Quite a few shops here if you need them, including more built into the Bridge itself.

path: A beautiful path runs alongside the bay here, with views back to the .  Look out for the whimsical sculptures hiding in the garden on the land side of the path.

Maryugh Railway Station, Station Street : Maryugh’s iconic railway station was completed in 1890. Take some time to admire the intricate tessellated tiles, elaborate entrance  and also the longest station platform in country Victoria.

Memorial Cairn ,  Street : 1939 monument commemorating the  brothers: first white settlers of the Maryugh area back in 1840. Some of the stones are from the original . Climb the steps for a sweeping view.
Box-Ironbark Avenue: Walk the Box-Ironbark avenue between the tennis courts and Jubilee Oval and see if there are any blossoms attracting nectar-feng native birds.

Lake Victoria: Walk the willow path round Lake Victoria and pass by a playground, covered bbq facilities, Caravan Park and camping area, sporting s, fishing boardwalk and many species of water-loving birdlife.

Outdoor Olympic Swimming Pool: A heritage-listed 1940 Art Deco building hs the public outdoor pool area. With dense lawns, specimen trees and 3 sete pools, it’s one of Maryugh’s favourite places in the Summer months.

Princes Park historic rotunda & gstand: The historic rotunda was built in 1904/1905 to commemorate Maryugh’s Golden Jubilee. Look out across to the ornate gstand and lush grass of the Princes Park sporting oval.

Memorial Gates to Princes Park: The impressive 1885 cast-iron gates and pillars of  granite (c.1926) with the names of fallen WWI soldiers are a solemn reminder of loss in a community. Lest we forget.
Princes Park ticket box: This quaint ticket box was built in 1908 and is the only known remaining one still in operation today.

The Bull and Mouth Hotel: Admire one of High Street’s most ornate buildings, The Bull & Mouth Hotel. Built in 1904 with g features, a multi-million  project has recently been undertaken to restore its former glory.

Site 1 - Engaging the senses: The Market was part of the estate of the Aboriginal Wurndjeri-willam clan of the woi wurrung language group. The Market was in use 13 rs before it officially opened in 1878.
Site 2 - A place to meat: The Meat  or Meat, Fish and Rabbit Section as it is officially known is the oldest building on the Market site and was originally used as a whole meat market.

Site 4 - Deli des: The Dairy  is a wonderful intact example of an art deco building. Before modern refrigeration, marbel counter tops and special underground ventilation systems were used to keep products cool.

Site 5 - Produce and pioneers: The real history of the Market starts with H & I Sheds and A & B Sheds - used as an outlet for 's Market gardens, which were run by the Chinese, then later by Greek and In communitites.

Site 6 - 's Marvellous Meat : In 1884 a new front to the Meat Market was added. The Meat  is both of architectural and social significance for its rarity as one of a few purpose built market buildings in existence in ia

Site 7 - Market football: By the 1920s, a strong sporting and social culture had developed among the stallholders and merchants at the Market. Football, cricket, bowls and golf clubs were formed with matches held in 1920 - 30s

Point 8 - Instant and delicious: By the 1950s, food vans became a popular fixture. To satisfy the tastes of Amn servicemen stationed in  ng World War II, cafe menus were expanded to include cola and hamburgers.
Site 9 - The Old Cemetary: Much of the Upper Market is situated on cemetery land. Although closed in 1854, some families with vaults and reserved allotments were allowed burials up to 1917.

Site 3 - More than a facade: The facades are of architectural significance as are the iron gates
under the Produce Arch and between the shops and the Meat .
Queen Victoria Market: The Queen Victoria Market, established in 1878 is the largest market in ia and one of the largest in the world. Many of the buildings are still used in trade today.
WCTU drinking : The  was erected in 1901 by the Womans Christian rance Union, who agitated for the provision of clean drinking water in public places as part of its rance concerns.

The Argus - corner  and LaT Street: The building hd the Argus newspaper for 30 rs. The Argus was one of 's three leading newspapers, all established the founding rs of the , until its closure in 1956.

The Welsh Church - 320 LaT Street: The first free dispensary for women in 1896 was set up here. In the first 3 months the clinic treated 2,000 women and children. This led to the establishment of the Queen Victoria Hospital.

Republic Tower - corner Queen and LaT Street: Public art where you would normally expect a billboard. Designed by  architect Nonda Katsilidis, various internal artworks have featured here. Cross the street for a close-up.

Laneway street art: Step into this laneway to see a fantastic public gallery of street art. A hidden treasure trove of quirky, odd and creative pieces guaranteed to raise your eyebrows in surprise and wonder.
Queen Victoria Market: The Queen Victoria Market, established in 1878 is the largest market in ia and one of the largest in the world. Many of the buildings are still used in trade today.
WCTU drinking : The  was erected in 1901 by the Womans Christian rance Union who agitated for the provision of clean drinking water in public places as part of its rance concerns.

A picnic spot: There's a table near the carpark that's perfect for having a picnic if the sun is out. Watch for lyrebirds that are known to frequent the area.

Viewing platform: There's a viewing point half way down the path that gives you a taste of the rambunctious river that's flowing at your side. Your ears will already know about this. It's very loud.
A lush staircase: As you descend into the rain, take care on the steps in case they are wet or slippery. Admire the lush tree ferns and Myrtle Beech that thrive in this cool dark world.
Viewing bridge: This timber bridge takes you across the Taggarty River, giving you the perfect viewing platform to watch the waves of fresh water gush be your feet.
Stunning : The Taggarty Cascades is an impressive site! Such a steady flow of clear gushing water tumbling over the granite s and down into the rain below.

HV McKay Rural Discovery Centre -  Run : ’s tri to the Sunshine Harvester, early pioneers and the sheep and grain industries.  Run is home to ’s Community Quilt and has a fabulous gift shop. Open 7 days a week.

Overhead Railway Bridge: The Overhead Bridge was opened on June 16 1928 (costing £454 to build) and removed Nov 24 1980. It was sold to the  Progress Association and today links  Run and the EPA Museum.

Railway Station Water Tower: Built in 1870 to supply water to steam trains, the 18'x15' tower was made from locally made bricks, with 27" thick walls. Water was pumped from the  River. ated to the EPA in 1972.
Railway Station: Opened 1870, originally named Runnymede Railway Station, the station was renamed  Railway Station in 1876. The Queen travelled by train through  on her 1954 tour.
Progress Association Museum: Situated in the Railway Station Buildings, this volunteer run Museum is free and well worth a visit.
Victoria Hotel-Motel: Built in the late 60’s to replace the gracious double-story Victoria Hotel.
Street: d as the main street & named after Rt. Hon. Ed , Secretary of State for the Colonies, 1864. Traffic flow altered when a new bridge was built & Margaret St constructed in the 60’s.
Plaque Project: Funded by property owners, the recently (2015) installed series of plaques relate the history of many buildings in  Street.
Former Parson’s Store: This store was established in 1893 and traded as a general store until 1982. Today, Parson’s Store is used as a display area, storage and workroom for the  Miniature Railway.
Michie Street: Named after Hon. Sir Archibald Michie, MLC, MLA, Attorney-General.
Athenaeum : Built in 1885 for £800, & opened in 1886, the Athenaeum  was designed by W.C. Vahland & built by Mr G. Galbraith.

and District Preschool: The Preschool was built as an Infant Welfare Centre (circa 1960s) and extended as a Preschool in 1972.

Law Courts: The building next to the Police Station was built as the Law Courts but is now privately owned and used as a Solicitors and Accountants office.

The Old Water Tower: Used to store the town’s water supply (pumped from the ) the pumping station was on rails to move up the bank in times of flood. The station also produced the town’s electri until 1948.
