: Even in the dry months of summer there are pools of clear water to dip your feet in on a hot day.
Ruins: Keep an eye out and on the other side of the gully you'll spot an old stone wall, half-hidden in the bush.
Wildlife: Small s are a common sight underfoot, and in the greener areas of the gully the odd wallaby can be spotted. Tos the end of the track you'll find this homely-looking cave on your right.
Breakneck Gorge: A p, tree-filled gorge that appears suddenly around a bend, Breakneck Gorge is a great place to watch birds in the treetops below.
Wild : This walk was completed by Wild , a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dcated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.
Space man: A vision of the future?  Who, what, where and how - well that's best left to the imagination.
Worm wall: Wall full of lyrical whimsys.  Get up close and you'll find out who's lamenting what and other funny sayings.
Taxi rider: Is the cat innocent or constor in this midnight adventure?

Lemming wall: Who's naming the lemmings?
Lemmings or meerkats?  Where are they going? Lemme know!
Amnesty Internal wall: Fantastic series of wall panels describing the work of Amnesty Internal (it's where their office is).

Mermaid under attack: So much to marvel here.  Make sure you look up and around.  Also check out the laneway nearby too, it has lots of hidden secrets!

Thank goodness for colourful and creative types.
Place: Check out the back wall of this park. Are the pictures of local residents?

Playground: Let your child run free in this well designed playground. There is a range of different equipment for climbing, swinging and exploring. Includes a swing with harness and double-width slide.

Bird hide and bng: This bird hide is the perfect spot to have a look at who might be nestling or feng in the water. You might like to have a look at the tree farm near the bng to see what's growing there too.
BBQ, seats and shade: This is the perfect spot for a picnic, BBQ and to refill your water bottle.
Beautiful gum trees: There are many beautiful gum trees lining the side of the ovals and creek. A shady spot and a great reminder of how the looked before it was colonised.

't feed the birds: Contrary to popular opinion, it's not healthy for ducks and birds to eat bread. This can lead to poor health, loss of hunting and foraging skills, and dependence on humans. See link below.
y Club: Stay away from the y paddock is s are in action! Obviously, 't cough or sneeze too close to them either, in case ....
Dog training: Furry friends of all colours and sizes are often seen in the park. It's a popular spot for dog walkers.
Under the bridge art: Clearly, the artist feels an affinity with the furry creatures that frequent the area.

Glass Creek revegetation works: A beautiful array of genous plant seedlings were recently been planted. These include River Red gums, native grasses and bottlebrushes. This area should look spectacular in a few rs.

End of path: The path ends rather abruptly at the road. Council have painted a section here but there is no footpath. You can continue on here carefully, or take the long and scenic route back the way you came.
Aquamoves  : First of all the path takes you past the Aquamoves swimming complex, which has a variety of different pools and playgrounds. Entry is via Tom  Drive.

's All Abilities Playground: This playground is a good stop for the kids. It has tables and chairs, toilets, water s, slides and all kinds of play equipment. Children are required to have adult supervision in the park.
The Jetty: A boardwalk allows you to walk out over the water. The wood can become slippery when it is wet and ther aren't guardrails all the way along it.
Canoe Club: At the waters edge near the canoe club there is a  and a small boat ramp. There is also toilets near the canoe club.

Cafe and Greater Sheparton Visitor Information Center: At the cafe there are indoor and outdoor tables as well as toilets. The cafe provides the opportunity to purchase a drink and take a break along the way.
The visitor centre is next door.
Picnic areas: Along the track there a number of BBQ areas with tables and facilites.
Skate Park: The skate park is a popular park for the  children and the big kids too. There are occaslly competitions held and there is always sne to watch.

Slavonija deli: This deli has an unassuming exterior, but inside, it's full of deful treats.  I particularly recommend their boreks and poppyseed rolls.  Closes around 2pm so make sure you get there early.
Mumbai Mirch: Spices, sauces, pickles, herbs, snacks, pots, pans - everything you need to make a delicious an meal.  Next door's restaurant is simple and tasty, though service can be a bit leisurely.

Hanna's coffee: Hanna opened this coffee shop maybe 4 rs ago.  It's a busy place stocked with nuts, interesting biscuits, sweets and magazines.  Regular patrons are the older fellas from the former Yugoslavia.
Cake shop: This shop has a fine display in the window.  Filled with cakes, rolls and a few Vietnamese buns, it's always a good place to stop to check out what's on offer.

Vietnamese deli: There are all sorts of mysterious and delicious food items here.  Some are sweet, some savoury, some both sweet AND savoury!  I 't quite remember what they're called so I just point at what I want.
Ha Noi Pho: Tucked in a laneway is my favourite Vietnamese restaurant.  The owner Dao is lovely and hospitable.  The pho is terrific. My favourite dish is lemongrass beef wrapped in vine leaves.
Chinese chess: If you loiter long enough, you might learn how to play Chinese chess from one of the locals.  A popular pastime for the blokes visiting Alfrieda Street.

Chilli bakery: I usually have an egg and salad roll from here, though there are many variations to choose from.  There is a  wait as this is probably the most popular place for Vietnamese rolls in the area.
Fish : There are a couple of fishmongers on this side.  I try to pick sustainable fish from ia (snapper is always yummy).

Vietnamese grocery stores: This is one of many Vietnamese grocery stores in the area.  I like checking out the aisles of cans and bottles from different places.  There's plenty of fresh veg that I've never seen elsewhere too.
Shady seats: Take a seat here and stop to watch the crowds go by.
St Albans market: St Albans market has cheap and fresh fruit and veg.  Unfortunately there was a fire recently.  I hope it's open again soon!

Down the track: There’s something special about this track, as you find yourself coming close to farmhs while at the same time fng yourself in the middle of a vast view.

Follow the fence line: There are tracts of this walk that take you through mowed paddocks, mostly along the fence line but then cutting through paddocks, s and nearby farms. It feels good to take this stroll.
Who was CJ ?: Once you’ve e this walk, you may wonder how  got its name. Interpretative signage will give you the answers you’re looking for.
Ring Road versus tranquility!: It is an interesting juxtaposition – the big busy noisy freeway versus the small peaceful walking track. I know which one I would rather be on!
Ducks and ducklings: The river and wetlands is swarming with birdlife, we were lucky to be there to see this family of duck and ducklings.
Lots of  in the wetlands: Depending on rainfall the rivers and ponds can be plentiful with lots of lush foliage surrounding them.
e Street Reserve: This Reserve has it all! Big new BBQ area, skate park, playground, heaps of grassed area and even 2 flying es!

Turn right and cross the bridge: When you get to the bridge, turn right to head tos e Street Reserve. If you want to head straight check out the walk “ Ponds Creek Trail – ” as this is its starting point.
You take the high road, I'll take the low road: Again, you have options where to walk! Take the low road (right hand) and follow the valley to continue with this particular route.

While the cars slog away above its peaceful down here!: At this point of the walk you are basically directly under the Western Ring Road. If you wish you can turn left here, go under the Road and head south, however to continue with this route head straigh
So many options where to walk: There are lots of signs along the way showing walkers where they are where they can go – almost too many options!
rt Booth Reserve: Start at rt Booth Reserve. Bus stop on Clow Street. The reserve offers an off-leash dog park, playgrounds, sporting s and an athletics track.
A lush start: This part of the walk is particularly leafy and green. Enjoy the shade!
Watch out for trail regulars: This walking and cycling track covers  north and south, so you're bound to spot cyclists and joggers in training along the creek path.
Art sculpture: As you walk tos  Road, you're bound to spot the Freedom Cycle sculpture. A bright cut-out style design of a cyclist taking off out of a yellow square!
Underpass at  Road: Walk up onto  Road and down to the underpass on the other side of the creek. Avoid the underpass if flooded.
A swimming spot?: We're not sure if this is a good idea but we have seen it with our own eyes! Sne went for a quick dip in the wetlands and we think, lived to tell the tale.
Handy signposts: If you're keen to get your bearings, there are signposts dotted along the creek trail, with distances from major roads and venues. Handy if you're keen to walk further!
In search of shade: Wetlands are typically shrub-filled spots, so it's always a relief to find a huge tree offering shade for many. Stop here a while if the sun is high in the sky.
Playground: This is a wonderful playground for all ages, with toilet facilities nearby.
Covered BBQ area: After a long walk, catch your breath over a BBQ lunch or have a rest in the shade. We spotted two studious locals studying outdoors the day we visited. Great idea!

Stadium: One of the largest stadiums of its kind in the southern hemisphere, you might like to explore this venue, visit the cafe or use the facilities. It's said to attract 15,000 visitors each week!

Sandridge Bridge: Sandridge Bridge used to be the gateway for Port  trains cng the  River. Now it hs ‘The Travellers’, giant steel sculptures representing immis to our shores.
Pony fish nd and Pedestrian Bridge: Pony fish nd is perched under the Pedestrian Bridge that is weighted down by s hooked on by lovers. The Eureka Tower dominates the background.

Inner - Gary Deirmendjian, 2005: Made of , the installation aims to evoke and question the tensions between one's objective and subjective realities - the former striving for perspective and the latter for engagement.
Meant To Be - Colin Langridge, 2005: Mean To Be is the result of developing the cooperating process of wooden construction, where bent wooden laths are shaped to form hollow containers.

Zephyr - Tim Eds, 2005: Zephyr is a sculptural self portrait by Eds. The interface of the human and the machine is a source of contemplation acting as a metaphor for production, astion and restriction.

The Comrade's Re - William Eicz, 2004: This popular 19th century genre is reintrepreted in an eclectic and contemporary way, deliely references antiquity and unfashble ideas of heroism and folly within a camp and knowing artifice.

Ether - Ari Purhonen, 2002: Ether embodies an optical effect produced by the natural phenon of . Rotating vertically around the axis, the illusion is created by an optical interference patter within the sculpture.
Death of white good - Alexander , 2005: Far from the chaos of an airline crash, Death of a White Good is a picturesque ruin. It is unclear if seconds or millennia have transpired since the crash.

As weeks go by - Laurens Tan, 2004: As Weeks Go By represents 4 weeks of time as they disappear before our eyes, including the opportunities built into each day as represented by omly perforated cans.
Meniscii -  Davis, 2007: Meniscii explores the perceptions of, and relationships between objects, spaces and places. In particular the relationship between the earth and the sky.
Migration - Ian Burns & John Clark, 2005: Migration is concerned with movement and the relationship between the vidual components and the mas they represent in formation.
Meanwhile... Down South in ia - Bob Jenyns, 2005: This sculpture explores the way in which aspects of history repeats itself, often in unexpected and ironical ways.
Hut - Karen  2000: Hut symbolises the h, the home, the shack, the cubby-h and he hermit's retreat. It also alludes to the potential to dream that is inherent within all of these structures.
Fractal construction - David Jensz, 2005: The curved form of Fractal Construction approximates the end of a massive pipe projecting from the ground.

Prosthetic apartment B - Richard Goodwin, 2004: Prosthetic Apartment B is an installation which creates a building within  Park. As a site-specific work it brings the idea of habitation to a public park.

Portal to another time and place - Dah Halpern, 2004: As related by Halpern, her work is 'An arch in the shape of a face, leaning on its nose. To see something whimsical, surprising and deful in the landscape is always inspiring'.
Swarm - Nigel Helyer: Swarm consists of a series of laser cut acrylic objects closely resembling microscopic marine forms, each supporting a solar powered digital circuit, amplifier and sr.
Exoskel pod - Richard Goodwin 2000: Exoskel Pod speculate about minimum architectures and the point at which the body stops and architecture begins.
Remannt - Mike , 2004: A burnt gum tree gives Remnant its primary form but the work has much to do with historical allusions as natural forces.

Upperground - Ewen Coates, 2006: Upperground resembles a cathedral structure; raising questions about the relevance  of the church and evolution of tradil teachings, in an era when religion causes schisms in our world.

Passage - F Orr, 2002: The concept of the frame has strong associations with history, painting and museums. Orr's been developing sculptural frames over recent rs and is interested in taking the frame out of the gallery.

Rothko's chapel - Konstantin Dimopoulos, 2007: Rothko's Chapel is a dynamic sculpture exploring and expressing through colour, line and movement, the simple and reverential colour variations of wned 20th century painter Mark Rothko.
River: Take a rest along the river and enjoy the scenery.
Wall - Mark Stoner, 2002-03: Wall is suggestive of great density and permanence; it is tough and uncompromising in its form - asserting itself within the landscape but remaining sete from it.

Mansion: Built in the late 1880s by the  brothers, ful pastoralists from Scotland. The  family lived here till the 1920s. The site was later used as a seminary by the Cic Church.

Grahams Wetland Reserve: Wander through a vast area of wetlands, with the You Yangs in the distance and boats bobbing in the bay to your left. It's largely unsigned and without paths, but impressive all the same.
Boat Ramp: Beside the wetlands, where the  River meets the bay, there's a marina of jetties and boats waiting to set sail. Excellent pathways and facilities here, if needed.

Look out for birdlife: Look out across to the pointy sandbank on the other side of the river mouth. Here you might spot birdlife relaxing on the shore. This area is home to flora and fauna unseen in other parts of the bay.

market gardens: There aren't too many places in the world where vegetables grow across the road from a beach! With 41% of Victoria's food grown in this region, it's a good time to stop and savour what's around us.

Memoral  (former picture theatre): The  Memorial  was built in 1920 and is used for all sorts of social functions including a local emergency centre ng the floods of 2010/11 and was originally a country cinema.

Superb Fairy Wren: Fairy-Wrens are just one species of the nume birdlife that can be spotted in this area and makes a walk just that bit more enjoyable, especially when they stop by to spot you.

Perfect : You may choose to wind down at the end of the day to watch the sun sink below the horizon, reflected on the water’s surface.

Planning a picnic?: Whether you eat first and then walk, or reflect on what you’ve seen over a tasty meal after you’ve discovered this beautiful reserve, the facilities are kept clean and comfortable.

picnic area: Tables, toilets and picnic shelters are provided.

Track sign: From here you can cross the bridge and go to  or continue to your right and loop back to the start.

Creek: This creek was severely impacted from muddy water being washed into it but today it looks clean and healthy.
Sandy creek bank: A sandy spot  by the creek  to rest or picnic.
Water hole: Perhaps have a swim?!
The end: Follow the creek back to the bridge back to the beginning.
Ocean  Surf Beach: This is a beautiful beach for walking and playing. The sand is so soft and the views of the Barwon  are exquisite.

Sand Play: If your kids want to play in the sand then stop for a rest. It is so therapeutic for kids to play in the sand. Try and keep your kids off the dunes  though. There is a good spot later on this walk!
Bridge: This bridge is great fun to photograph and the kids really love walking under it.
Between the : This section of beach is really fun because there is a large deposit of sand here and it is ok for kids to play here without damaging  the dune system.
Ocean  Surf Beach: It is so nice to run in some open space!
More sand play: Kids can never get enough sand play!
Along the Barwon River: The tide will dictate how much sand you have to walk on but walking on s is always an option!

Wildflower 1: As you begin the walk, you'll notice the variety of plants growing on each side.

Wildflower 4: These are s. I have them in my front yard. The purple flowers are great. Plus, they're a very  plant that will grow in the toughest environment (eg. my front yard).

Wildflower 8: Trusty s. The smell of  is refreshing.
Wildflower 9: We found these on our way to the beach.

Gateway Lakes precinct: Gateway Lakes hosts a large number of events and activities each r and is home to ’s water ski, canoe, dragon boating and rowing clubs. Take a s detour and check it out!
genous art and history : Look out for the genous cultural displays along the trail as you enter into Harris Road. You will learn about our local history.
Picnic by the  River: Enjoy one of the many lovely picnic spots along the  River for a family picnic. Quiet, calm and very picturesque. Enjoy!
Wildlife spotting: Along the nature trail, keep your eyes ed for some local wild life – can you see a kan in the long grass, some new ducklings even?

Gateway Village precinct : Gateway Village has a lot on offer from yummy food, hot or refreshing beverages, art displays, theatre performances to the   Farmer’s Market from 8am every second Saturday. Visit www.hmfb.or
Mills Park Circuit : A glimpse of the green open space and lovely native trees. You are on your way.

White Necked Heron: With lots of wetland along the walk you have a good chance of seeing a Heron or two.  They spend lots of time standing very still, keeping a sharp eye out for frogs, insects and fish.
Echidna: If you're lucky you might spot an Echidna out looking for ants, termites and other small invertebrates which it captures with its long sticky tongue.
Walk markers: There are a number of markers along the way.  This walk follows sections of two walks - the Morang Wetlands Walk and the Ridge Track.

Sheoak tree: The mat of fallen branchlets under she prevents the development of undergrowth.  For aboriginal people it was considered a safe place to leave children as snakes are said to avoid these areas.
Kan Apple: There are lots of Kan Apple trees along the way, a hint of things to come further along the walk.
Beauty on a small scale: The wetlands support beautiful succulents thriving in the sow waters along the walk.
Park view: The walk s through a diverse range of bushland and wetlands.  Along the way you get a real sense of being out in the bush.
Eastern  Kans: Eastern  kans are gregarious and form open-membership groups. The groups are made up of 2-3 females and their offspring with the same number of males of which one is dominant.
Grasses and Sedges: The wetland areas support a wide variety of native grasses and sedges.  See how many different varieties you can spot along the way.
Wetland view: One of several small lakes along the walk.  Each one supports a wide variety of birdlife including Black s, ducks, Purple Swamphens, Egrets, Grebes and Eurasian Coots.
Black  and s: Like other s, the Black  is largely monogamous, pairing for life - there is apparently only a 6% divorce rate!  They also share parenting responsibilities of the s.

Dragonfly: Dragonflies usually patrol a particular area looking for insects to eat. Mosquitoes, flies and midges are a large part of their diet. This fact alone should endear these deful creatures to us!
Walking in open bushland: The pathway is a mix of gravel path and some more overgrown pathways like the one in this picture.  Overall the route is quite level.
Eastern Great Egret: The Great Egret breeds in colonies, and often in association with cormorants, ibises and other egrets.  Their nest is a large platform of sticks, placed in a tree over the water.
Foot bridge: Though the pathway is mostly quite wide at one point along the route there is a very small footbridge.  If you would rather avoid it, there is an alternative route back to the carpark.

am North Road car park: This car park was first provided in the 1980s, but was much enlarged for the Commonwealth Games in 2006. Sometimes crowded on weekends, it has the only toilets and water on this trip
Down in the valley: This section of  track is the lo on this trip. Watch for mountain bike riders, but also for wildlife in the mornings and evenings
Head of the incline: This landing was once the top of a 1 in 10 tramway incline. A 'powerful engine' once sat here to winch the empty skips back up. What kind of engine? We 't know!
The hidden quarry: A narrow defile on the right leads into the hidden quarry. This is not visible from the track, though walkers on the Rock Gardens track can look down from above

Tramway cutting: Tramline track does not follow the course of the old tramway at this point. The cutting on the right shows where it went. Cuttings were rare on tramways as being expensive to escavate by hand
Crest reservoir: This reservoir at the crest of the range is long out of use. What was it for? Walk from the north corner sly west of north across Ridge track...
Horse drinking trough: This cement lined drinking trough provided water for thirsty horses at the top of the long climb from the quarry. Still intact despite being out of use for over eighty rs
hills summit: The trig point marks the highest point of this range, with fine views through 360 deg, including  to the south, and the  of the north-west. The view is worth the 700 m walk
Les Stone Park Wetlands: A great spot to try your hand at fishing. Even better if you have  children as it offers a safe space to teach them the skills.
te Ship: This play area is great. A safe space that lets the imagination run wild. Grab your eye patch and perch a bird on your shoulder and see what adventure you end up on
Under road cng: Avoid cng this busy road by taking the opl path under the thoroughfare. Great low risk option for people walking with groups of children or animals.

Football oval: If you are walking along this path, why not stop for a kick of football on the way. The oval is well manicured and is home to permanent AFL posts. A little friendly competition never hurt anyone...

Nature at its finest: The path is edged by beautiful trees almost the whole way along. Providing much needed shade in the warmer months and an excellent display of colour in Autumn, they are also home to many types of Bird
Bird hs: Sne has built and installed some unique bird hs in the trees here. They're dated and initialled. I'd love to know who did this!
Skate Park: There is a skate park here that is incrbly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!
Netball courts: For anyone wanting to spend some time at a netball court, these are tucked away at  Park and there is a gate from the walking track to the park
The Aboriginal Cultural Heritage Trail: For those wishing to discover more about Gippsland’s rich genous heritage, this cultural trail is an excellent place to visit.
Bush tucker: Over 27 species of native plants are included in this garden, all with important roles to play for the Gunaikurnai nation.
A must for the keen BMX bike-rider: A busy place for the BMX enthusiasts and fun for others who just like to enjoy watching the skill involved.
Picnic and play: A fitness station for adults and children alike, and a sheltered BBQ area for those days when a picnic enhances a lovely walk.
Under the willow: One of many picnic table areas along the way is this beautifully shaded area under the .
Bev's Wonder World of Dolls: Open Tue-Fri from 10am to 3pm or by appointment at 31-33 The Boulevard, this is an extraordinary collection of dolls from around the world.
Walk among the gum trees: Remnant vegetation is home to nume animals, and the birdsong emanating from the canopy is a de to hear.
Bridge cngs: Along the trail, you will find  that can take you along the other side of the Waterhole Creek and back to the start of the walk (linked to the Gippsland Heritage Trail).
Fertile reed bed: The healthy mix of reeds provides habitat for a multitude of aquatic species as well as being useful in the g of baskets.

Surrey Dive: In its days as a swimming hole, the Surrey Dive had a fearsome reputation, and was the scene of several drownings. Today the scene is more placid, with model boats gliding across the water

Morning greeting: I'm not sure who this saint is but he looks like he's happy to be up early!
Reserve: There's a small playground here.  I wish it had a bbq and seats too.

School veggie garden: If you peek in the cracks between the fence, you'll see the school veggie garden! I think it would be good if the school had a wire fence so you can see what's growing in the garden.
Trugo Club: Whats Trugo?  It sounds In.  Must be a good game to play if theres a whole club set up for it!

Lawn Bowls Club: They play mostly on Saturday mornings I think.  I've seen lots of people here, in their best whites (probably why I'd never be able to play - all my whites are attracted to food stains).
Leisure Centre:  pool, spa and gym. Friendly staff, fun pool for kids and a much improved cafe.

Reserve: A lovely park to sit in, with benches, a weird sculpture and a bright red mural on the walking path.  There's also a monument to Harry (who's Harry?),  lovely flowers and a funny shaped tree.
Mall: A nice place to sit and listen in on the local gossip if you speak In, or Greek or Lnese?  Good spot for coffee and a great kb/falafel.  Post office is here too.

train station: You can book Vline tickets here.  Recent improvements with lots of new plants, sete lane for cyclists and better ing and disability access.  Good work!

/ Rd intersection: An apparent slip by 1888 surveyors resulted in 's worst intersection before the rail line went underground. Major collisions on the cng took place in 1926 and 1952, each claiming 9 lives
Road:  Ave was previously  Rd north and south of  Rd. The 1920s post office was on the south side, the 1970s post office on the north corner
station square: The retail complex on the  was built in the  early 1970s,  Mall in the early 1980s. The car park was re-modeled in the early 2000s. Some retailers have e better than others
Road: In earlier days Ringwood Rd,  Rd has been busy for many rs, though the shops have changed much. The site of Maguire's garage, long a local landmark, is now the Commonwealth Bank

rail station:  station was opened in 1920. The first station was burned down in 1971, and was replaced in 1982, burned again, a third station in 1988, and today's sub-surface station is actually Mk IV
Ave:  Ave became a retail area in the 1960s. It was home for many rs to  fire station. The fire brigade practiced in Maguire Park, where pranksters put detergent in the
Progess : The progress  opened in 1926, hosting local dances for many rs, and rallies in World War II. Damaged by fire in the 1990s, the  was repaired, and still hosts community events today

"Post Office Bell" 2008: Dr Anton Hasell created the bell.  Hassells "'Little Sister Bell" is suspended in the centre and chimes on the hour.  Atop sits the historic 1880's  Post office bell and a  figurine.
Jubilee  /  Regl Art Gallery: Jubilee  was opened in June 1924, the jubilee r of the Methodist Church next door.
Wesley Performing Arts Centre: Formerly the original  Methodist Church (opened in 1912).  Inside still today is the original pipe organ; the diapered designs on the display pipes are outstanding.
St Michaels and  Church: Built in 1987; the a winning design is the work of distinguished and internally wned ian architect Greg s
St  Uniting Church 1962: Designed by architect  Reed.  Much of the original stone from the old church was used in constructing the new building.  The stone was quarried from
Theatre: An outstanding example of the work of Bohringer,  and Johnson, one of the most important and prolific cinema architectural firms in ia
'Platanus acerifolia: Woven Nest' 2009: This environmental work by Michael Shiell was installed as part of 2009 "Art is...Elemental" Festival.
Original  Letterbox: This original  Letterbox inspired the design of the Post Office Bell sculpture in Firebrace Street.
Town  /  Regl Art Gallery: Built in 1938/39 as a municipal complex and was designed by  architect Charles  Hollinshed, who also designed Her Majesty's Theatre in
Roof Top Ribbon 1998: ng the 'Art is....Energy' Festival in 1998, New Zealand sculptor Jeff Thomson, "the undisputed Iron Man of asia", was commissioned to create a sculpture.

Boer War - Avenue of Honour & 'rts' Tree 1901: The only avenue to commemorate the Anglo-Boer war was planted in  in 1901.  The remaining elm  of the original Avenue was planted to commemorate   Lord rts.
Totem Pole 2000: Angie Polglaze was commissioned by the 'Art Is... A River of Time' Festival in 2000, to create this piece of Chainsaw Art.  It was carved publically and noisily ng the festival.

"Wimmera River Burnt Creek Meeting Place" 2007: The sculpture takes the form of a seating arrangement.  The work uses stone mosaic to depict the intersection of the Wimmera River and Burnt Creek as a meeting place of the 5 tradil owner groups.
Painted Tiles 1997: Images on the tiles reference chnages in   life through the seasons.  The pictures are the children's vidual reflections on their culture and environment.

Bradbury Lane Mural 2008: Local visual artist Nichola Clarke worked with youth groups from the area to create the Bradbury Lane Mural.  The instion for participants was to paint their idea of a future .

"Aerial" 2009: The metal sculptural mural "Aerial" depicts aspects of the Wimmera's unique landscape; a ravens eye view of the area made in conjunction with students of McKenzie  Creek campus of  College.
St John's Anglican Church 1957: Features an expansive wooden ceiling, various stained glass windows and two significant sculptures.  'Wayside Cry' and 'Compasste Christ'

Fishing Lagoon: This beautiful lagoon, surrounded by reeds is the perfect place to stop and try your hand at fishing. Shaded by beautiful trees, the picnic area is also a good place to stop for lunch.

The start: Start near the 'Princes Walk' sign in between  Square and Princess Bridge and walk down the path to the river.
Path to Birrarung Marr: Walk down to Birrarung Marr and you soon leave the traffic sounds behind.
View of the : Looking across the  river to the Boaths. If you walk in the morning or evening you will usually see rowers on the water.
Angel: An iconic  Sculpture by Dah Halpern.
The shady path to the bridge: The wide shady  path is gravel for the first few hundred metres before it becomes paved near Batman Avenue. There are some toilets on the left hand side.
Looking up the river: This magnificent view may help you ignore the traffic on the bridge.
High and low path: Once off the bridge, you can choose the higher more shady or lower path near the waters edge.
The steps: There are two sets of steps nearby. Why not go up an down them a few times to get the blood pumping!
The high path : More shade on the high path and a better view across the river.
Left before the Bridge : Turn left before the bridge back up to St Kilda Rd (or continue on to  and cross the river at the footbridge back to  St Station).
Princess Bridge: Cross Princess Bridge and you are back at the start, and should feel fresh and reinvigorated!
Information Centre: Marvel at our local talent in Stockyard Gallery or catch up with your facebook friends with free wi-fi in the Library. Community and tourist information available 7 days a week.
Pearl Park: Enjoy Harry the Miner's view of the vegetable and flower gardens or put a snag on the free bbq.
Stockyard Creek: The first alluvial gold was found in the Creek in 1870.  Can you spot a platypus - about as elusive as the gold!
Skate Park: Between the  Water Board and the Scout , we dare you to dangle your skateboard over the precipice.
Primary School: Site of one of the first Stephanie Alexander school gardens and still going strong.
Humungus eucalyptus tree: Wrap your arms around this ol' timer.
Adventure Playground: Swing like a possum or climb like a koala over this large adventure playground for all ages.  Situated in the  Showgrounds. Public toilets available.
Ambce Station playground: Through the Tassie Tiger gate, a fire truck and ambce are just waiting to be revved by  s.
Op shops: There are a few op shops along this road, all with bargains to be discovered.
Secret creek: This creek is quite hidden!  't quite know where it goes but is probably connected with the lake.
Lake Sanctuary: A beautiful lake, often with different types of birds and surrounded by a small pocket of .  Particularly atmospheric on foggy mornings as the mist rises from the lake.
Heritage Trail: There are a few signs marking the trail, but I'm not sure where the Trail starts or ends!
Playground: Playground recently given a bright red coat of paint.  Now it really stands out and gets the kids going.
The Pines  Citizens Centre: I've walked past and seen dancing classes and morning tea on offer. What else do they get up to here?
War memorial and tennis courts: War memorial and local tennis courts in the background.  A pretty garden and lots of places to sit and watch what's going on.
library: Lovely library with benches and mural.
French cake shop: This French cake shop has some amazing cakes!  I once saw a queue all the way outside around Easter time.
Op Shop: Bargains !  Great shops around this area too, including bakery, cafe, art shop, hairdressers and more.
Rotary Saturday market: There's a little market outside  station every second Saturday of the month.  Fresh fruit and veg, craft, plants and other bits and pieces.
Playground: Playground outside  station, a good spot for kids if you're waiting for the bus or next train.

View of Thompson River: There is a great view of the Thompson 
River and the new Pearson Cng Bridge to your right.
Revegetation of the Sanctuary: genous tree planting has been completed by local primary school children and  Shire Council staff.
Superb Fairywren : The Superb Fairywren feasts on insects. The males are bright b while female are brown.
Eastern Yellow robin: The Eastern Yellow Robin is a common resident of Herb Guyatt Sanctuary which hunts insects.
Azure Kingfisher: The Azure Kingfisher eats small fish and yabbies. You may see it as it darts between trees.
Lush : As you leave  North, you pass over some massive embankments and travel through a mix of remnant rate rain and dry schlerophyll .

The  Station & Picnic Rotunda: A great place to stop to learn more about the rail trail through interpretative signage as well as fng remnants of the brick kiln used to create nume culverts along the line.
s Bridge: A spectacular cng over the wetlands of the Little  River might entice you to take a break at the picnic table to watch out for an abundance of birdlife.
Post-fire  regeneration: This part of the trail has rebounded magnificently from the damage caused by the 2009 bushfires.
Cows in the reeds: Signs of farming appear along the trail, especially when you come across a herd of cows munching on the tasty greens of the wetland reeds.
The Rolling Hills: The Strezlecki Mountains became known by European settlers as “break Hills" due to the difficulty of eking a living from the steep, thickly ed, often sodden and remote country.
Daisies in the : Close to rra is a lovely stretch of , filled with wild flowers and swathes of daisies.

Welcome to rra: The old pylons of the railway are used as an archway as you enter Railway Park. As you approach, look for the interesting and historically significant brick drainage culverts under the trail.
Playground: Start from the play ground south of  round and east of Westfied reserve. Walk West along the asphalt path  avoiding left turns down .
Turn right here: Turn right just after the oval onto a concrete path (POI 2) between the oval and building. Cross  Bend Road (a very small road) and follow the path south along Merri Creek.
Viewing platform: A nice spot to stop for a picnic or to enjoy the view.
Path tos the : This (POI 3) is my preferred path into the .  You can then take  Street West which is quite pleasant.
Bridge over the highway: The second option (POI 4) appears preferable - you 't have to cross Alexander Pde, and you spend more time on park, but can be jarring once you reach Hoddle Street.
The Rushes: Simply gorgeous parkland full of native plants and grasses. It also has an outdoor gym. Stop here to listen to the sound of twittering birds. Very relaxing!
Bottle brushes: Bianca Boulevard's man strip is planted with flowering bottle brushes, which when in bloom, look spectacular.

The Ruins - Davis Park Heritage Area: Here lie the remains of a b stone cottage built by the Davis family in the 1850s. There used to be a cellar, dairy, irrigation channels, wells and more.  See boards for more information.
Orchard: Look closely and you'll find various fruiting trees, including lemon, apple and olives. The park also has a cricket pitch outdoor gym, BBQ, seats and shelter.
yle Avenue Park: This park has lots of seats and a fabulous playground. It's right next to the yle Country Club though entry is limited to lye Estate residents only.
Davis Family Park: This park has a variety of features for outdoor recreation - ovals, basketball, playground, outdoor gym and climbing frame.
Birds of dise: Davis Family Park has fabulous plants that are colourful and unusual.
Map of  in 1981: The  Historical Society have included a map of the  area from 1981. For more information on the History of  see the link below.
Emerson Place Reserve : The walk begins at Emerson Place Reserve across the road from the  Village Shopping Centre.
Emerson Place Reserve Playground: Enjoy time with family at the Emerson Place Reserve Playground.  Council has  over 200 play spaces in parks and reserves.

Outdoor Gym : The first outdoor gym in the  of  is now ready for everyone to use, for free! The outdoor gym consists of four sete stations in an easily accessible circuit. See website below for details.
Liberty Avenue Reserve shared path : Follow the shared path to Liberty Avenue Reserve.  has more than 100kms of shared paths that connect with major parks, reserves, schools and shopping precincts.
Outdoor Gym : The next outdoor gym station at Jackie Close Reserve features a body dip station and two sit up benches.
Outdoor Gym: The next outdoor gym station at Liberty Avenue near Magna Place consists of step ups, pull ups, leg raises and a stretch station.
Outdoor Gym: The Liberty Avenue outdoor gym consists of a body twist, multi bars, eliptical trainer and leg press. It also features a set of instuctions on how to use the equipment.
Liberty Avenue Reserve Playground: Enjoy time with family at the Liberty Avenue Reserve Playground.

Liberty Avenue tennis and basketball courts: Enjoy a game of tennis or basketball at the public courts located at Liberty Avenue Reserve.   Council provides a wide range of leisure and recreation facilities and programs.

Track sign and No. 5 Brace: The building in the distance was a sorting plant for the coal, operating from 1909 to 1968. For hundreds of 14 r old boys this was their first place of work as they picked stones out of the coal.
Pioneer Mines Area : This is where it all n. Mining commenced in 1909, producing 780,000 tons before closing in 1914. Underground workings were very sow, evident by the depressions in this area.
Overgrown path: Keep a lookout for this sign post. The red arrow points right, so take this  but narrow and overgrown path.
Fallen tree branch: You may encounter a natural obstacle on this track as it takes you into  of the heathland.
Western Area Haulage Line : A 3km rail track where skips were hauled overland by cable. Have a look for the cable on the ground. Pine trees line both sides of the track.
s Beach track : After you cross the road there is an option to walk to s Beach. The red track to s Wetland is clearly signed and heads to the right.
Nos. 9 and 10 shafts: Together these mines covered an area of almost 200 hectares. Thats 160 underground cricket grounds! The coal has gone but this concrete shaft remains.
s Wetland and bird hide : Nesting boxes and permanent water make this a perfect home for many birds and water fowl. Watch out for Pacific Black Ducks, Purple Swamphens and White-faced Herons.

Street track entrance : Leave the street and follow this gravel track back into the heathland. On the right is the Cinder Loop track which formed part of a horse drawn tramway used for transporting bricks.
Tent Town : The site where 12 miners first lived when the State Coal Mine opened in 1909. By mid 1910 the township of  was established with the construction of 100 miners' cottages.
Amazing large mural by Smug, 2016: This is a massive and striking piece of art by artist Smug, of his own gparents.
Uniacke Court - Art by Deb: Some great pieces of art by Deb, a  artist now working in te US. Some of these are from at least 2010, but still look fresh.

Dosa Corner - an restaurant: As the name suggests, this place specialise in Dosa - thin, crispy pancakes served with a filling and a selection of tasty sauces to be mopped up. I can't go past a Masala Dosa - spicy potato filled.
Gardens: 's oldest park and a beautiful open space. So named as it was the site of a  erected in 1840 to allow the  to communicate with the port.
Nomads back bar: This alley was one of the locations of this rs Meeting of Styles festival, an internal street art event. This alley hosts artwork by Dvate, Adnate and French artist Choq.
Muleta's cafe alleyway: Another MOS site, this back alley is overflowing with  coloured and fun pieces of art, including some great paste up work.
Blender Lane artists studio: A studio, hosting some of 's most up and coming and established artists , this lane is forever being added to and evolving. An excellent spot for stencil art.
Queen Victoria Market: 's most buzzing market - not open on Monday or Wednesday's though. Also open evenings with live music on some nights - check their website.
Redleap Reserve Northern Playground: An adventure climbing playground close to the lake and picnic facilities
Public Art Pieces: You admire the public art, like 'Brolgas and Eggs' by artist Kevin Free
Redleap Reserve Nothern Picnic Structure: Facilities include seating, electric barbeques and cover structure
Peter Hopper Lake: Peter Hopper Lake supports plenty of bird and animal life
Hungry Ducks and Water Birds: Bring along some food for the birds if you enjoy getting surrounded by hundreds of hungry mouths
The Stables Shopping Centre: This shopping centre has just about everything.
St Francis of Assisi Primary School: There are plenty of quality primary schools in the local area
Primary School: There are plenty of quality primary schools in the local area
Roycroft Kindergarten: Support your local childcare services by strengthening the concept of community
Roycroft Reserve: Behind the the playground, you will find two football s and connections to a greater network of walking paths
Mimosa Park: A fantastic setup for a park. Barbeques, full-size basketball court, plenty of open space, playground and plenty of paths for the kids on scooter to roar around on
Mimosa Park: Have a shoot around or cenge others to a game
Primary School:  Primary School supports walking and safe routes around schools
Safe Routes to School: These recommended cng points not only educate kids about road safety but show s that there could be children cng also
Community Centre: This centre is used by  groups, special interest groups and activity groups. Facilities include 5 rooms, kitchen and outdoor area.
Preschool: Another service in such close proximity to other community services
Aquastyle Swim School: Learning to swim is a life-saving skill

rrin Centre, Dr Harry Jenkins Reserve and the  Tennis Club: The recreal opportunities are quite endless in the  area.
rrin is an Early Childhood Intervention Centre, providing services to children with developmental delay or disabilities.
Native grasses and bng: View across the bng to Papillon de.
Playground and outdoor gym: There are also seats and a BBQ.
Farfalla  Way Park: A you-beaut playground, with BBQ, water , basketball half-court, seats and shelter. A perfect place for a rest, picnic or family get together.

Overlook of Playground Reserve: This is a very nice overview look of the playground reserve in the park which includes plenty of playground equipment, free public sheltered barbeque, bins, nicely cut grass and water s.
Oval: One of the best ovals around. This one looks very nice and green with very finely cut grass. Looking good for ball games and running.
Bundoora  Art Centre: This art centre is a historic h gallery with a cafe and free admission. The front garden looks amazing.
Beautiful looking h: This h or mansion was the finest looking in my opinion out of the already nice looking hs in the street and area. I thought it was a hotel.
Electric towers: Two electric towers located close-by  just on the edge.
Mount Cooper scenery view: A very nice distant outlook from the top of . A lot can be seen from here. It's 137 meters above sea level- the highest point in 's metro area.
Lake: This lake (or pond) had many ducks swimming in it. The bench there was great for sitting down, relaxing, and seeing the ducks.
Electric towers: Two big electric towers close-by  just on the edge.
Information Hut: At the day car park there is an information hut with toilets and a big map to help you find your way.
Map of  Village and walking tracks: This walk goes through the  bog reserve, onto the red lined 4WD track then to Charmichael Falls.
Playgound and picnic area: Right next to the information hut and sign posts is a playground, giant chess board and picnic tables.
Vehical access  track: This track loops the village and takes you to the start of the Charmichael Falls track.
Fallen Tree: Much of this area was cleared to make a fire break to protect the village from the 2012 summer bushfires.
Start of the Charmichael Falls track: Look out for this sign on your right and follow this path.
Track markers: Look out for these  markers hanging on the tree trunks to guide your way.
Natures colours: The colors of nature change with the seasons.
Secret falls: Look out for the unmarked fork in the path leading down to another mini falls.
Mini falls: The fresh snowy water g it's way down the mountain.
Hazard: There can be water on the track in places.
beauty: The highland scenery.
Bog track: Turn around here so you can take note of  to the  Bog track on your return.
Zig- Zac down the mountain: The track cuts back and  down this steep section to the viewing platform.
Viewing platform: Just a little way further down the track is this viewing platform.
Charmichael Falls: As seen from the viewing platform.
Tree tops view: From the viewing platform you can see for  over the undulating mountains and tree tops.
Bog Reserve: Turn off to your left and follow the track through this permanently wet area which supports rare flora and fauna.
Hidden  wetlands: There are several ways to access these wetlands, best to jump in and start exploring.
Keep your eyes open: Even a bird this small can catch your attention! This fella was chatty and chirpy, posing for a photograph.
Pencil Park playground: Look out for the towering pencils in different colours. The playground nearby is great fun too.
Covered BBQ facilities: With the playground nearby and so many walking paths on the horizon, this is a handy spot to have a picnic or bbq and let the little ones play.
Golf Club: Walk along the south perimeter of the parklands, you'll spot the lush greens that belong to  Golf Club. Follow this path along until you reach the start of the next wetland area.

Tatterson Park wetlands: As you wander through the Tatterson Park wetlands, envious of the homes on either side, look for other homes of the watery variety. A family of black s have taken up residence here.
Chirpy residents: As you walk, see if you can spot some of the native birds in the area. Black s are easier to see than some of the smaller varieties. While others are louder than most!
B sky view: A footbridge in the centre of the park offers a sweeping view of the wetlands.
Springers Leisure Centre: This is the perfect spot for an air-cioned rest, a cuppa and snack. You might even shoot some hoops while you're here!
Beautiful walking trails: Be sure to wear a hat on sunny days. While there are trees closer to the woodland area, it's pretty steamy in full sun along the wetlands walking track.

Tatterson Park Community Sporting Complex: You can't see it right now, but if you look south to the two ovals in the distance, that's where a b new sporting complex is set to be built in 2016. Stay tuned!

World of Insects: Quite possibly the cutest playground in the world, this one features ladybugs, ants, beehives and a giant magnifying glass! The design was chosen by the community and has an environmental theme.
Arachnophobes beware...: Just joking. These spiders are for climbing on! Bugs too. Another aspect of the World of Insects playground in Tattersons Park. Not everything's cute it seems.

20-hectare woodlands: Maurie Jarvis Woodland is named after a councilor and three-time local mayor who had a passion for native trees and their preservation. More than 20,000 genous trees were planted here in 2005.
Transition into wetlands: It's here on the edge of the woodlands that the wetlands begin. A stunning transition.
One of many playgrounds: This playground is closest to  Boulevard. There's a big tree nearby and a duck colony too.
Distinctly different wetland: Cafardi Boulevard offers a different style of wetlands, at first, as it moves away from the rich woodland of Tatterson Park. Follow the street to reach Hidden .
Dlly Town : It was the original County Court from 1884 swapped functions and became the Dlly Town  in 1890.
Dlly Museum: Dlly Museum is home to the anvil that the world's largest nugget (69kg), 'The Welcome Stranger', was cut up on in 1896.
Original streetscape showing Coach Office and Billiards buildings: Original streetscape showing Coach Office and Billiards buildings and part of TP  General Merchant.
Dlly Post Office 1892: The Dlly Post Office was built in 1891 with the c installed in 1949 as a Second World War memorial as well as the soldiers plaque in the front wall.
Lon Chartered Bank: ‘The Welcome Stranger’ nugget was brought to Dlly to be sold at the Lon Chartered Bank in . The building is now a private residence.
McBrides Ironmonger: The two-storey ironmongery shop and dwelling was built in 1863 by Peter and Catherine McBride, who came to Dlly from Scotland in 1857.
Footers Mansion 1865: Once a privately-owned g h, it is now a B&B.
Dlly Uniting Church: One of the few buildings in Dlly that hasn't changed its use!
Wesleyan Jubilee Sabbath School 1886: A very g building that is now used as an op shop.
Belleville 1869: Owned by politician James Bell and designed by a local store keeper, Thomas Tyrer.
Original Dlly Town  1862: The town  was complete with a public library and reading room, as well as council ch and offices.
Up 1863: The  Up was built as one of the police and court buildings on the government and legal precinct on Market Street. It was used until the Dlly Court closed in 1981.
Police Station 1958: This is an example of a typical 1950s standard rural area police station.
Land Titles Office: It was also a Postal and Telegraph Office 1872-91
Post Office: Lands and Survey Office 1861
First Court H, County Court 1858: The former County Court H was constructed of coursed bstone by James Nichols. It is now a Masonic Temple.
Chauncy Cottage 1859: Chauncy was District Surveyor from 1861
Noisy Miner: Not to be confused with the Common Myna, the native Noisy Miners assist each other to raise their .  They form large groups and actively defend their territory.
Heathlands: The last section of the walk winds along the edge of beautiful native heathland that supports a wide variety of fauna. A large section of heathland is fenced off for conservation.
Wooden Sculptures: Just as you set out on the walk you will pass by two beautiful new sculptures of native fauna.
The track: The track is very level and well maintained throughout.  Just make sure you have brought a hat for sunny days.
The Bird Hide: The bird hide gives you the opportunity to watch birdlife undisturbed in their natural habitat. An information board contains pictures and names of all the bird species you might see.
Great Egret: There is a lot of birdlife living among the wetlands including the Great Egret (pictured), ian Wood Ducks, Black s, Pelicans and many more.
Shared path: You might meet the occasl cyclist traversing through the park at a very relaxed pace.

Salinity and Trees: When salty groundwater comes to the surface it can be too much for some trees as this group detrates.  Rangers and volunteers are planting thousands of trees to keep the groundwater low.
Kan Apple: The Kan Apple adds a wonderful splash of colour to the park when in bloom.  The fruits were eaten by Aboriginal people, but only when very ripe, as they are poisonous at other times.

Echidna: If you hear a rustle in the grass it might be an Echidna out looking for lunch.  But if he hears you he will quickly try to hide.  If you see one, please keep your distance, they are very shy.

K Club Rush: Very  and ful near coasts.  It helps to bind sandy soil, is also good for getting rid of polluted water.  Aboriginal people used this in combination with sedges for weaving.

Dog Whelk and Cockle Shells: Shells can tell some interesting stories. Dog whelk (right) drill holes into cockles through their shell and then into their flesh. The flesh weakens from pressure, the shell opens. Dinner time.
Start of the walk: At the start of the walk there is a very good information board giving details about the walk.
Picnic Bench: Just inside the gate there is a picnic bench in a lovely setting.  A good spot for lunch when you return.
Coastal Woodland: This is the last remaining section of coastal woodland on the  Peninsula.  There is a vast array of genous plants along the way.
Gnarled Tree: This particular tree cannot be missed on the walk.  It tells the story of a hard and windswept life.
Beetle cng: Watch your step as you walk along the path.  You might encounter very interesting insects braving the open plains of the pathway to find food on the other side.
Bench: A bench immersed in local flora, where you can sit and take time to spot some of the abundant wildlife that this coastal woodland supports.

Small Leaf Clemitis: From July to November you will see cream, star-shaped flowers in abundance.  Male and female flowers are borne on sete plants.  The Aborigines ed and kneaded the tap root to make dough.
Marshes: Great views of water filled es great the walker when you leave the coastal woodland.
Pelicans: Look up!  Pelicans normally fish together.  They herd fish into a central position, and then plunge their bills into the water to capture a fish.
The boardwalk: This fabulous boardwalk allows the walker to explore life in and around s.
Beaded Glasswort: Beaded glasswort is abundant around the boardwalk. Their seeds are a major winter food source for the very rare -bellied Parrots who migrate to  Bay from ia each winter.
Grasses and sedges: Grass skinks and tiny birds shelter and forage among grasses and sedges.  Butterflies lay eggs on sedges, a food source for their caterpillars.
The G Hotel : Originally the G Hotel was known as the Coffee Palace.  The change of name to the G Hotel occurred in 1920. Head inside to see historic pictures. See walk description for more.
Feast Street : ’s iconic restaurants, The new Spanish Bar and Grill, Seasons and Stefano Cellar's.  This end of Langtree Avenue is fondly known as Feast Street.

The  Brewery :  Brewery is the original site of the ‘hard top’ Wonderland, a wintertime cinema. Its name was changed to the Astor in the 1920’s and recent vations have preserved parts of the old cinema
T&G building : The T&G building on the corner of Eighth and Langtree has a distinctive c tower. In the 1920’s it was the site of the Zimmers Building.
Hudaks Bakery : ’s bakery institution, Hudaks. It started life as Bowrings Buildings. The lane behind the building is still named Bowrings Lane.
Shillidays Corner: Site of ’s old department store Shillidays.  Shillidays ceased operation in the 1980’s. A  walk down from Shillidays Corner is the store Doug nes. It was the site of ’s Bakeh
The Ozone: Where Rockmans is now located, was the site of yet another cinema, the Ozone. It closed in 1971, choosing the film ‘Ryan’s Daughter’ to say goodbye with.
Banjo’s Bakery : Banjo’s Bakery was once the surgery of ’s first resident dentist, Claude Sutton. Mr. Sutton practiced here for 50 rs.
Dr. Abramowski’s Chemist: Where the  Bank stands was once the site of Dr. Abramowski’s Chemist, sirly to Mr. Sutton, he was the first physician in the town and he gained an impressive reputation.
Fire Station : On the left, 89 Langtree Avenue marks where the  Fire Station stood from early in the 20th century until 1980, currently Tristar Mcal Centre
St.  Church: Across 11th and left tos  Ave is the Uniting Church, known as St Andrew’s. It started out as a Presbyterian church and was built in 1914, at a cost of 2097 pounds.
Public Offices: Across 11th Street are the  Public Offices.

Sacred Heart Peace Memorial n Cic Church.: Across 11th St is the  Cic Church.  In 1896, a wooden structure was built in Pine Ave & in 1924 that building was relocated to this site. In 1921 the original brick church was built.

Cic Church and Presbytery: The neighbouring presbytery was erected in 1935. A walk inside the church is welcomed and the 14 Stations of the Cross, fine timberwork and stained glass are worth closer inspection.
Lime Ave: Lime Ave was once a primarily residential street but is now an extension of the commercial centre. Places such as the Ball Ballroom, a popular dance spot in the 60’s are long gone.
Nash Building: The Nash Building, named for G.A Nash, the original occupier of the building. Th building was completed in 1917, however the Nash Backery and Grocery business dates back to 1888.

Telephone Exchange: Opposite the  Brewery is the Telephone Exchange. In 1910 it was the site of Wonderland, an open air cinema.  Entry was 1 shilling for adults, 1/2 for children and 2 shillings to reserve a chair

and  Statue: Designed by Charles Summers, costing ₤14,000, the statue was unveiled on 21 April 1865, four rs after the fateful exption. It has had many  locations and was installed here in 1994.

From the 1920s-1940s, many legendary Aboriginal srs such as Pastor Sir Doug  addressed gatherings here.
The Koori Club, 43 Gertrude St: Established by Aboriginal artist, Lin Onus, this was a social and political meeting place ng the 1960s for  people infnced by the Black Power Movement.

Aboriginal Housing Board of Victoria, 79 Gertrude St: This was established in 1981 to advocate for Aboriginal families, whose needs were not being met by State housing services, resulting in high rates of eviction and homelessness.

Victorian Aboriginal Legal Service, 11 Brunswick St: Established by volunteers in 1973, this service sought to combat disproporte and unjust impacts of the legal system on Aboriginal people in Victoria.

Victorian Aboriginal Child Care Agency, 5 Brunswick St: Established in 1976, this agency took steps tos healing effects of racist Government practice and policy that saw setion of Aboriginal children from their families (see: Stolen Generations).

Gardens Housing Estate: ng the 1980s, this was a popular and safe meeting place for homeless Aboriginal people as well as other Aboriginal people looking to find family and community. See 'Stories Around the Fire' video

Koori Information Centre, 120 Gertrude St: Established in the early 1980s, this was an effective coordination centre for Aboriginal political activity that eventually attracted unnted covert surveillance by federal police.

Victorian Aboriginal Health Service, 136 Gertrude St: This was the second site of the Health Service, considered one of the largest and most important Aboriginal organisations to have emerged from Fitzroy.

Fitzroy Stars Aboriginal Community Youth Club Gymnasium: The Youth Club gym (184-186 Gertrude St) was established in 1977 as a preventative health program to combat the increasing drug and alcohol problems within the metropolitan Aboriginal community.
George  Hostel, 66 George St: This hostel was initially established as a half-way h (in 1974) to support the increasing numbers of homeless Aboriginal men in and around Fitzroy.
Ninbiya, 99 George St: Established in 1983, this was a local community meeting place where Aboriginal people could gather to practise arts & crafts, play sports and have a feed.
Builders Arms Hotel, 211 Gertrude St: Known as the 'Black pub of ', this was an important social and political gathering place for Aboriginal people from the 1940s until the 1980s.
Victorian Aboriginal Health Service, 229 Gertrude St: Established in 1973, this was the first Aboriginal community controlled health and dental service in ia.
Koori Kollij, 42  St: Established in 1982, Koori Kollij was an Aboriginal health worker training program that forged new and enng standards of Aboriginal healthcare in ia.
Victorian Aboriginal Co-operative Limited, 108 Smith St: Established in 1976, this co-op provided local housing and welfare services to the Aboriginal community of .

Pastor Doug  Church of Christ, 258  St: In 1943, Pastor Doug  and his wife Gladys , with support from the Church of Christ, established a church service that attracted a devoted Aboriginal congregation.

Jones Reserve:  Jones was a local resident that set aside the land for the reserve when it was threatened by development many rs ago. It has a lovely playground but no bins so please take your litter home.

Delbridge H, 55 Carlsberg Road: One of the most extraordinary and intact ultra-modern homes of the 1950-60s, the floating structure and all-glass appearance, was achieved only by daring structural engineering.
Desbrowe Annear H - 38 The Eyrie: Built in 1903, the h was designed by Harold Dsebrowe Annear, one of ia's leading and most innovative Arts and Crafts architects of the early twentieth century.
School of Art: 'The  School' refers to artists in the 19th century who were inspired by the beautiful landscapes of the  River and the unique  that typifies the ian bush.
H - 32-34 The Eyrie: Designed by Desbrowe Annear,  H incorporated Modernist ideas and Meval-inspired design principles and was infntial in the developmentof the Art and Crafts movement in ia.
Steps: The road now turns into a pocket park full of bushes and trees. Follow the path down the steps for a walk amongst the trees. This will take you to the next h.

H - 32-34 The Eyrie: The third of Desbrowe Annear's designs,  H is of architectural significance as a particularly good example of a work displaying the early expressions of modern architecture in ia.
Lookout: A good spot to lookout tos the  river and Bullen Park and imagine what the landscape used to look like.
HIlls: The hills are an excellent workout. Imagine how fit you would be if you walked this area every day!
Place: Named after Walter Burley  and  Mahony , who advocated garden  planning and the idea of a neighbourhood as a physical and social planning unit.
The Righi Reserve: A lovely playground with plenty of shade. Perfect for a picnic.

The Eagles - 32  : An unusual and eclectic inter-War villa with many distinctive details including vermiculated rendered panels, elliptical arched entrance porch, wrought iron balustrading and leaded windows.
Dowling Avenue gardens: Lovely cottage gardens, and a very spectacular gum tree that looks burnt (but probably isn't).
Sports Reserve Trail: A pleasant and popular trail with walkers and dog owners. The reserve has a cricket oval, seats and shelter, tennis courts and a playground.
Playground: Cute little playground for er children, and possibly grown ups who like using some of the equipment to help them with stretches.
Tennis Courts : A family ed club catering for players of all ages and levels. There are 6 courts. Lessons available and competitions are organised to help sharpen your skills.
Box Place Kookaburra: This kookaburra has found a beautiful garden to rest in. A wonderful example of a low maintenance yet deful garden.
Jillard Walk gardens: A spectacular little pocket of gardens! Take a stroll to admire the fantastic range of bushes and flowers planted here.
Carruthers Way Gardens: More lovely gardens to walk past.
River: Heading east, you cross over a number of  but the first one across the  Valley floodplains involve an impressively long bridge utilising the old railway trusses and pylons.
Wonderful wetlands: No need to wade through water to enjoy the experience of being within the midst of nume birds and aquatic wildlife!
The great ian pie!: Welcome to Glengarry, which has a bakery famous for its tasty pies that are well worth g a stop to experience (Bushies Bakery at 19 Main Street).
Sea of poppies: The diversity of agriculture in the region is beautifully illustrated by this  of poppies that are grown for mcinal purposes as well as being a superb sight in bloom.
Wide open road: At Toongabbie, the trail opens up to become a wide boulevard and the historic township is worth taking a side trip to explore.
Home is where h is: Against a backdrop of farming enterprise, you will come across nume examples of historic ruins that speak of this region’s rich history.

Things you can do with a soup can: Just one example of the many innovative sculptures you’ll discover along the way is this upcycled representation of a cow, paying homage to the days when  was home to a busy butter factory.
Art Space: Internally wned artist-in-resident Clive -White opens his studio at the  Art Space to show interested parties the magic of transforming stone into sculpture.
The Dawson Connection: Take some time to wander around the adjacent Flora Reserve before heading onto the quiet back roads tos  and then returning to the gravel path.
Wetlands: This is an excellent spot to pull over to enjoy the sound of frog song at  and a rich habitat for birdlife at any time of day.
Birds Land: This well equipped picnic area is the starting point for this heritage walk. Birds land has BBQs, toilets and shelter, and is only a  distance from the main road in
Lake circuit: The flat and well maintained paths around the two lakes are the most popular local walk. There is much birdlife, and many wayside seats at which to stop, rest, and take in the view
Retaining wall: This flood mitigation basin was constructed in the early 1980s. The nearby gate is a meeting point for several tracks: Nixon Road to the north is steep
n's : Thomas n 'selected' this land and built a  in 1845. He drowned attempting to cross  Creek in 1862. His widow re-married, to rt Nixon, and is buried in FT Gully cemetery
Strettle's granite: Abraham Strettle purchased a property in this area in 1866 and called it 'Strettle's granite'. The view from the tors to the north and west is worth the steep climb from n's track
Abrahams track: This section of track is sheltered on a warm day. The farm on the other side of the fence is modern, but evidence of earlier farms is just around the corner
track:  track descends steeply to rejoin the main trail to return to our starting point at Birds Land. The dams beside the trail are evidence of earlier farms, and now home to nume frogs
Mt Gor: This trail begins by walking in the direction of Mt Gor, with a street of hs on the right and  Street above on the left.
Lyrebird prints: Gilberts Gully is home to many lyrebirds. Look for footprint etchings in the red earth. If you listen you might just hear their distinctive call.
Wilks Creek: The first of two cng at Wilks Creek, which was named after the engineer Clement Wilks who designed  and culverts in the 1860s that opened up access to the Woods Point .
Spongy fungi: As you walk, be mindful of what's be your feet. A pile of dry leafs can often be a home to another organism, in this case, a bright yellow fungi.
Mixed-species : The trail continues up a small sloping hill, with tall manna gums pointing sky and a thickening blanket of tree ferns covering the ground below.
Cng Wilks Creek again: This end of Wilks Creek is more vibrant and fast-flowing. The water is per and it seems more likely that other species might call this spot home.
Native birds: If you're lucky, you might spot some of ia's native birds, like this beautiful Crimson , which paused just long enough for a photograph at the end of the trail.
station murals: A huge w, by Makatron, and a whole host of other fun pieces of art to brighten up the daily commute.

The Corner Hotel's car park: One of 's best known venue's for up and coming bands, this place is home to some excellent nights. ng the day, check out the car park which is full of art, including a large piece by Bode
Lou Reed tri: Take a walk on the wild side and enjoy this monochrome Lou Reed tri piece.
Super wall : Need I say more? You may be lucky enough to spot an older piece of work by te here too.
Racehorse mural: A piece of public art that is regularly defaced and then repaired, because not everyone thinks horse racing is a good thing. Pretty cave painting kind of style to my mind.
The green wall!: A wall that has been covered by a number of artists, almost exclusively in shades of green. The centrepiece is a tri by artist Dvate to his father.
Heesco, Putos and Mysterious Al wall: A collection of pieces that I always ejoy seeing from the train on my way into town!
Coe and Coe cafe: This place does amazing sandwiches and great coffee. A regular spot for  shock artist Lush - love him or hate him, he does make me laugh!
genous boy by Adnate: The eyes - I can't help but wonder what this innocent  boy is thinking whenever I see him, wonderful wall.
Kwik Kopy: What a striking feature this building has been transformed into thanks to Beastman.

Start walk in Batman Park opposite the General Store: At Batman Point, enjoy the view of the paddlewheels of the P.S. Ozone paddle steamer off shore and the information board. Walk north along the trail to Batman Rd. Public toilets only on foreshore.

Batman Rd lookout over Half Moon Bay and P.S. Ozone Memorial: This lookout over Half Moon Bay is the highest point in . Relax and enjoy views of the  skyline and the anchor of the Wreck of the P.S. Ozone.
Batman Road : Batman Road is a wide road. Enjoy walking on the nature strip or the road edge. Go west on Batman Rd 200m to Ibbotson St or 700m to the  Woodland.
Ibbotson St. Alternate route 800 metres to Mc St.: Ibbotson Street bypasses the  Woodland and connects with Mc Street, a  trees conservation area.
Batman Road to  Woodland: Proceed west on Batman Road to Seascape Drive and enter Seabreeze Estate with the genous  Woodland.
Seabreeze Estate and Seascape Drive: Proceed south along Seascape Drive and view the significant  Woodland and the wetlands basin with its abundant birdlife.
Woodland: The 13 hectares of  Woodland contains River Red Gums and Coast Manna Gums plus Golden Wattle and Hedge Wattle. Sun Orchids in November.
Glenrana Drive - 600 metres: Proceed south and continue to Glenrana Drive with its wng path to Ibbotson Street.
Ibbotson Street - 300 metres: Once at Ibbotson Street turn south/right until the next intersection and proceed east at Mc Street.
Mc Street  1 Km: Mc Street is a beautiful conservation area, lined with arching  trees. Due to the  trees high environmental va, the street has no through traffic but welcomes pedestrians.

The Esplanade -  Reserve: Once at The Esplanade cross over and view the historic Batman Memorial and relax under Cypress trees in  Reserve Re-connect with the coastal trail and proceed past the BBQ shelter.
Coastal Trail - 600 metres: Proceed north along the trail and view the historic boatsheds and cypress trees and the main swimming beach.
Coastal Trail to rigging area & : Cyclists continue behind the Boat and Yacht Club buildings on the foreshore, walkers can proceed in front to Batman Park.
IH Boat & Yacht Clubs and  Community : The much loved Community  has panoramic views of the Bay. When nearing the boat ramp look out for boating activity.

Batman Park Camping Reserve: Back on the coastal trail, Batman Park has campers from November to April. The Wreck of the Ozone will come into view signifying the end of the Beach 2 Bush Walk. Public toilets and BBQ here.

Beautiful native plants populate the park: A dcated Friend’s Group ensures that the vegetation within the Park is both diverse and appropriate to the area, with so many magnificent flowers such as this beautiful .

Bush tucker: An excellent interpretive sign provides an overview of the plants that have a range of uses for the Gunaikurnai nation that has lived in this region for thousands of rs.
Gone fishing: Anglers can choose from one of five fishing platforms, with the  Valley Fly Fishing Club and Associated Angling Club regularly stocking the lake with  trout and redfin.

Bird hs: Sne has built and installed some unique bird hs in the trees here. They're dated and initialled. I'd love to know who did this!

Skate Park: There is a skate park here that is incrbly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!
Picnic and BBQ area: The oval along with the children's playground and BBQ area make this a great start/end point for a walk and for a picnic with the family
Park Beach South: Not for swimming (dange currents), but great for walking.

Along the : The path is great (good for prams). Sometimes waves can splash over the , on a warm day it is a de!.
Eddies in the water: Sit on the  and watch the waves curl around into this . The waves form eddies and patterns in the water. Very mesmerising.
