Willy Wagtails: You are sure to spot Willy Wagtails darting about.  When feng they distract insects by wagging and fanning their tail.

The walking route: The route is flat and accessible to all.  It is mostly paved and has very well maintained gravel tracks.  A  section at the end is not readily accessible by wheelchair, and can easily be avoided.
Cumbungi: Around the first small pond there is lots of Cumbungi growing.  It provides protection against bank erosion and is an excellent nesting site for water birds.
Riverside pathway: The path alongside the river is a wide shared path.  There are also sections of gravel path nearer the river bank as an alternative to the shared path.
Lounging by the lake: This recently developed area provides some wonderful resting options, fit for giants.  There is also a cafe in the apartment b behind.
Little Pied Cormorant: Cormorants and seagulls spend time resting and socialising around the moorings here.  The cormorants dive in sow waters to find fish and crustaceans.
Wetlands: Built as part of the nearby apartment development, the wetlands cleanse the stormwater entering the river and provide a habitat for wildlife.
Masked Lapwing (or Plover): Around the lake and bng is a feast of birdlife, including the Masked Lapwing (pictured), Eurasian Coots, Purple Moorhens, Seagulls and Ducks.
BBQ Area: Near the end of the walk, and close to the car park, is a BBQ area with park benches and a drinking water .  A great place for a picnic after your walk.
History of the Land Garden: The gorgeous garden is a patchwork of small ornamental gardens and mosaics.  Information boards describe the many uses of the area over the rs.
Mosaic: One of the many colourful mosaics in the garden, depicting Aboriginal life before European settlers arrived.
Bstone : The first of two bstone   you can turn left here, cross the ford and turn left again when you meet the river to make a er version of the walk.

brook &  Neighbourhood H: This organisation is made up of residents who live in brook and  and surrounding areas and are committed to listening to and representing local people to build a proud community.
Wheelbarrow Garden: Check out some of the wonderful gardens, like the wheelbarrow garden, on the walk. Very inspiring!
Cao Dai Vietnamese Temple: Cao Dai is a new religious movement founded in Vietnam. It was established in the  of Tây Ninh, southern  Vietnam in 1926. Admire the topiary dragons!
Blooming Roundabout: Enjoy the view of the roundabout, planted by   Council and maintained by local residents, before you turn right onto Churchill Avenue.
Council Public Art - People: People created by TRUC artists, Jo Leahey and David Burrows and made with corten steel.
brook Library: brook's first library has transformed the community. , old, and everyone in between make their way to the library to read, relax and connect with others.
brook Com Community Garden: The garden was set up by   Council to help improve food security in brook and surrounds.  The garden members are now an incorporated group. Join up and grow your own food!

brook Park/Skinner Reserve: Enjoy a wander around the park, walking and talking with friends.  Breathe in the fresh air nine kilometres from the  centre. Join in a kick of the footy or soccer ball and get your heart rate up!
Viewing platform: Before you walk down to Steavenson Falls, visit the look out for a stunning view of the valley below. The 84-metre-tall falls has a r-round flow due to its ed catchment.

Information: The falls begins its descent 350 metres higher up, on the crest of the Great Dividing Range. It drops 84 metres into a catchment of 16 square kilometres and supplies the town of  with water.
A gentle path: Follow the gravel path down tos  for a spectacular view. The falls mark the most dramatic point in the journey of the Steavenson River as it flows north to the town of Buxton.
From a distance: Observe  from a distance for a sense of just how tall they really are. Keep watch for wildlife and you may see a platypus in the river pools nearby.

Turbine generation: Walk along the lower path to access the turbine generation. At the base of  is a small weir that collects water, sending it down a 300mm-diameter pipe to power this hydroelectric turbine.
Water power: This cross flow turbine is believed to be the only one of its kind in ia. It was upgraded after the Black Saturday bushfires so that excess power could be sent to the nal power grid.
One of : There a couple of ponds in the Gardens with water birds and s.
Restored garden: Museum Victoria restored the former German Garden of the Western Forecourt in 2009, it was a carpark covered in asphalt.

Playground: A great playground to bring children to on the weekend?

rail station: This was the terminus when the line opened in 1889, and starting point for 'Puffing BIlly' for many rs. Part of the walking track back to the start are on the old rail right of way

genous Flora Reserve: If you choose to walk on the gravel path, watch out for signs providing information about plantings and other items of interest.

om art: Great to see that  is not immune from street art!

: The original  burnt down in 1952. Its replacement features a mural, stained and etched glass screen, pipe organ and sculptures. See the Trial of Socrates above the main entrance.
Architecture Building: Originally designed in the 1960s by then Professor of Architecture Brian Lewis, with a 1990s addition by Daryl . Within are several sculptures.

Eight hour day plaque: Commemorates a stonemason\'s stop work in 1856 which launched the campaign for the 8 hour day, an event of internal significance in the history of workers\' cions and industrial relations.

Cussonia Court: Named for the Cussonia Spicata tree gracing the middle of the courtyard. This tree was propagated from a cutting from the original tree planted in the 1880s by one of the Ursity's first professors
Court: The pillars in the middle of the courtyard and at the eastern end are relics saved from the original Gothic Revival style  .

Union H: The original building hd the Nal Museum (now Museum Victoria) from 1863 to 1899. Only a few fragments of the original building are still visible. Gallery on level 2 features contemporary art.

Underground car park: An engineering innovation using mushroom shaped columns to support the roof and accommodate drainage for the lawn and trees above. It's atmospheric interior featured in the ian film Mad Max.
Gatekeeper's cottage: Built in 1860, the cottage was a residence up until 12 rs ago.
Ursity Square: The Alan Gilbert Building hs ia's first large scale building-integrated photovoltaic solar power generator which won an a for sustainable architecture.

Frank Tate Building: Built in 1939, it was originally part of the  Teachers' College, this Art Deco building is now home to a learning centre for students providing vidual and collaborative learning spaces.
Sidney Myer Asia Centre: Built in 1999, the Centre is home to the Asia Institute and Asialink. The Centre prmotes public awareness and understanding of Asia.

Town : The  Town  hosts a shows for a variety of ages across the r, and the rails are great fun to play on. Have a look down the side of the building at the Black Saturday Memorial

Sheep Dog and Sheep: It could be a little difficult to get a pram or wheelchair in this entrance. The  Botanic Gardens are a great place for children of all ages to play and explore.
Botanic Gardens: The  Botanic Gardens are a great place for children of all ages to play and explore.

The trailhead: Here's the start of the 2km trail, it's hidden on the left with a small car park attached. There's a Keppel Falls Lookout 350 metres further along Lady Talbot Drive, not to be confused with this walk.
Roaring river: As you walk, the river will be beside you. Chances are, you'll hear it the minute you start walking on the track. It's a great view from up high on the path.
Afternoon frost: Even if it's sunny, there's a chance you could still see frost on logs and s that are closer to the river. This photograph was taken at 3pm on a sunny autumn day. Brrr!

Fallen Manna gums: Many trees have been felled in the area, but there's a healthy undergrowth that keeps this walk lush and cool in rature. Admire these once proud Manna gums, tall enough to cross the river twice!

Signs of regrowth: After the Black Saturday bushfires of 2009, the nal parks have needed to regenerate themselves. Everywhere you look there are signs of the past and future, in the towering trees and vivid ferns.
Keppel Falls: The falls were discovered by the Keppel brothers in the early 1800s. After the rains and the snow melt,  drain the nearby mountains into the  River.
Leave before dusk: This walk takes you down into a valley, so it quickly becomes dark the minute the sun sets behind the mountains. Be sure to head back to the car park before dusk.

Pause Spot One: Take 5 p breaths. What can you
See
Hear
Smell
Touch
Taste
p belly breathing and focus on your five senses. This is a popular way to relax and bring you into the moment

Pause Spot Two: Looking for Colours.
This can be helpful when your mind is going in circles.
Can you find something that is:
Green
B
Red
White
Yellow
What other colours can you see.

Pause Spot Three: Listening for Sounds
To fully in the moment we need to stop and absorb what is around us.
Listen for these sounds:
Birds 
Water 
People 
Traffic

Pause Spot Four: Take a moment to be grateful and reflect on your strength.
Say to yourself, I am strong like this tree because ............
Take a moment to be grateful and say to yourself, I am grateful for ......

Pause spot Five: Count your steps to the next pause spot.
Shift your weight from one foot to the other and walk with awareness one step at a time and count your steps until you reach your next spot.

Pause Spot Six: Congratulate yourself you have reached half way.
You achieve so many things over your lifetime. Take time to acknowledge them. Now turn and walk slowly, mindfully and enjoy the walk back.
Big Hill Track West,  : The walk begins at the carpark for Crusoe Reservoir & Number 7 Park.

Water Race In Use: some full!
Track Intersection: Take the track to the left at this first intersection.
Water Tank: After the yellow gas pipeline sign, turn right and head tos the water tank.
Dam Wall: The track goes between a small empty reservoir on the left and this brick building on the right.
Old Fence: At this landmark, continue straight ahead.
Fork In The Track: Turn right here and continue back to the beginning. The Number 7 reservoir will be on your left.
View along the way: Number 7 Reservoir
The Ol' Duke Hotel: The hotel and related buildings are a part of 's history. Enjoy music by an open fire at the Nal Celtic Festival.
The Ol' Duke - H Street side: Admire the excellent restoration and redevelopment of an historic building.
The  RSL Memorial Garden: This building was formerly a Nal Bank and hs a collection of military memorabilia.
St Patrick's : This church  dating from the 1940s has unusual, harlequin glass windows and is still an important community meeting place.
Tradil timber hs: This is a small enclave of tradil timber hs, especially lovely in autumn when the leaves are on the ground.
Intersection of H and Smythe Streets: Be careful cng this road!
Cng Smythe Street: You are leaving behind timber 19th century domestic buildings for large modern mansions.
Arlington Rise Development, turn left at the flags: Experience a good footpath on this side of the road.
Across the roundabout take the ups curving footpath: This path will take you to a deful small rest place and garden, with a spectacular view over  Bay to the You Yangs.
The park at the top of : Catch your breath and take a well-earned rest here!
Breathtaking views: A beautiful view at any time, but a great  experience! Return to e Street where there are a number of enticing places where you can enjoy your choice of food and drink.
Train Station Precinct: The Visitor Centre located here and can provide loads of information about  and the surrounding areas.
Masonic : Look for this building as you head east on the Western Highway. It’s stand out paint work makes it very easy to spot! Turn left into Queen Street.
Langi Morgala Museum: This red brick and bstone building was built in 1874 and boasts a very interesting history.  It opened as the Langi Morgala (Home of yesterday) Museum in 1970.
Astor Cinema: Completed in 1938 in the art deco style, The Astor was one of the largest purpose-built cinemas in rural Victoria. It closed with the advent of television, but re-opened in 1959.
Shire : The Shire  was built in 1871 – arguably one of ’s most distinguished buildings. The building hs a WW1 honour board and a beautiful stained glass window that honours the fallen.
Cenotaph: The monument was dcated in 1930 to those who served ia in various conflicts and in memory of those who died.
Town  and War Memorial : The Town  was built in 1869. The , planned to mark Queen Victoria’s diamond jubilee, also commemorates volunteers who fought in the Boer War.

Street with Vine covered veas:  Street showcases many historic buildings and the vine covered veas of the modern businesses. The first vine was planted in 1874 by Mr Grano outside his mixed business store.

Public toilet and seat: Here if you need it! A small detour will take you to the Bull and Mouth Stables.  Built in 1866 these bstone stables were described at the time as “one of the finest in the country”.

Nurses memorial – View Point: The memorial was erected to the English-born nurse th Cavell who was executed in 1915 for assisting prisoners to escape from the Germans. Each Anzac day a nurse lays a wreath in her memory.

Historic buildings - Vindel H: On the northern side of  Street, pass  Vindel H. Constructed in two parts, the Sub-Treasury and Assay office in 1858 – the post office was attached in 1862. The  c was installed in 1890.
Water station: A modern and thoughtful addition to the street provides the means for walkers to refresh and refill! Leave the main drag at this point and turn left into Ingor Street.
Gum San Chinese Heritage : This dramatic two-story building with its authentic Chinese tiled roof hs a fascinating selection of audio-visual and static displays. Well worth a visit!
J  - Lunatic Asylum: Completed in 1861, this building was originally a  prison. From 1866 to 1991 was the only institution in Victoria entirely devoted to the care of the criminally insane.
H: Completed in 1886 in the Queen Anne style it operated as a general hospital until 1937. Since 1988 it has been used as administration offices and a nurse education centre.

Alexandra Gardens: The Alexandra Gardens is home to the Active Pathway Project consisting a multi use pathway around the perimeter of the lake, two exercise stations, a wetlands boardwalk and better wayfng signage.
Celebratory Coffee: Head back to your car after leaving the gardens, or if you are in the mood, try Fred and Bet's  for a great coffee and an indulgent treat.
Star reserve: This reserve dates from the 1970s, but contains Aboriginal bush tucker sources, and also remains of the  military camp, built in 1942 to protect  from Japanese invasion
Tirha wetlands: This wetland is named for the  occupied by Rev. James Clow, first European settler in the  of , 1838. The wetland are  home to much bird life, and aquatic species such as frogs
incline tramway: This is the only incline firewood tramway in the  of . The home owner has a wood fire or stove, and has constructed a 15 metre winch hauled tramway out of angle iron
Police Road ret basin: This massive retaining wall was constructed in the 1970s for flood mitigation by the  Valley Authority. The DVA was absorbed as part of  Water in the 1990s

Magic 1278 transmission towers: These radio broadcast towers were constructed in the 1970s for AM radio Magic 693. Today operated by Magic 1278, transmissions from here are so powerful they can be picked up (just) in Antarctica!
Kilcatten Park site: Kilcatten Park  was built by James Quirk in 1856, and home for many rs to the Golding family. The  has now vanished, but exotic fruit trees still mark the site
VFL Park: This arena was to be the home of ian Rules football, staging the G Final and provided with its own rail line. Today, a moldering section of gstand is all that remains
Wonderful shady seat: On a warm day, this is a great seat to sit and watch the world go by.
The playground: There always seems to be children in this playground.
Looking back to Apollo Bay township: The path looking back to Apollo Bay township, the  knolls make wonderful slopes for rolling down.
Heading tos  River: I love this part of the walk where you start to get inviting glimpses of the sea and start wondering what lies beyound the trees.
The  river: Through the shady path and the  river appears, Marengo lies in the distance.
Dogs swimming: Not sure if it is an official dog off leash area, but there always seems to be dogs here.
Expansive views and little rock pools.: The ocean and sea breezes (sometimes gales!). The rock formations and great for hopping along and see things in  pools.
Collecting cuttlefish and shells: Lots of things to keep children interested, shells, birds, cuttlefish shells and general stuff to pick up and look at.
The : The stonework on the  is truly a work of art!
The end of the : Who can resist wallking to the end of the ? Great fishing spot too (caught a flathead there).
Shelterd harbour beach: Beautiful sheltered beach with crystal clear water. When we were there, two nesting Cape  Geese cmae hissing tos us.
Craypots, fishing boats and anglers.: The piles of neatly stacked craypots and fishing boats in the water are really beautiful.

Apollo Bay beach: The beach is most sheltered nearer the harbour and the swell gets bigger as you walk along the bay. It is a great beach for swimming, body surfing, surfing and flying kites (it can get very ).
The skate park: I love stopping and watching skaters, scooters and bike riders mucking around on the skate park.
The seals sculpture: Next to the Tourist Info this is the first of many fantastic sculptures along the foreshore.
Seat and sculptures: The  area across from the shops is a fantastic place to wander, stop, picnic and sit. If is also quite sheltered from southerly sea winds.
North Boundary Track: Lookout which offers 360 views of the Churchill , & you  can see all the way out to Stud Road
Car Park Entry: There is parking out the front of the park on Churchill Park Drive which offers easy access to the hiking trails
Army Track : You'll find many of the trails around the park quite wide with a loose gravel surface
Wildlife: The park has an abundance of wildlife & quite a serene & tranquil place to visit
Fauna: The park is full of hidden wonders
Escarpment: 's Creek cuts through the so-called "new volcanic" layer of basalt that makes up most of the terrain of the Western Suburbs. You can see plenty of volcanic features like this outcrop.
The Weir: This Weir has been here for a fair while, and nearby is a strange bstone box contraption that was probably a sheep dip. Cng over takes you to a silcrete quarry. Beautiful red gums abound.
Native Vegetation: As well as magnificent gum trees, there are native grasses, wildflowers and shrubs.  Council,  Water, and the Friends of 's Creek actively care for the grasslands.
Housing: People who live along the creek have been g their backyards their front yards so that they can better engage with their local environment.

Tool Scatters: This whole area is very important for the Marin Bulluk clan of the Wurundjeri people, and has been inhabited for ten of thousands of rs. 's Creek silcrete  is found for kilometres around.
Have a seat: Sit on the bench and enjoy the view
Wildlife : There is always plenty of birds and animals around. In this case a  Argus butterfly.
More trees: This stretch of the creek is particularly blessed with big trees.
Ochre: As we get further downstream, we get per under the basalt, revealing layers of gravel, Silurian bedrock, and this amazing ochre wall.
Birds: Red-rumped parrot
Up : It's pretty steep up that hill. Have a breather on a sly different seat.
Nature's Art: Sculptural forms
View across to the Wheel: A great place to start, if you are going to do a brisk walk, you might want to time yourself to see how fast you go for the next time you do the walk.
lunch spot and flower bed: Why not stop and smell the roses? Great water side view on this lawn area makes a pleasant lunch spot.
The wide boardwalk: There are quite a few seats or benches along this stretch if you need to take some notes on your walking meeting.
Harbour Esplanade : A favourite leg of the walk with many other people out on a lunchtime walk. Time to talk, think or simply turn off and get some exercise.
Table Tennis: Anyone for Table Tennis? Bring a work colleague, some table tennis bats and balls  and have some fun!
Cow up a tree: Cow up a tree by John  is a wonderful public sculpture. Look up every time you walk past and see if it makes you smile.
Monument Park: Another interesting spot to stop for lunch. Sit on the lawn or bench look at the artworks and enjoy the view.
Silence: 'Silence' by Adrian Mauriks is a fibreglass sculpture along New Quay Promenade. It's nearly time to turn around. Why not pick up the pace a little and get the blood pumping?
Looking South: Always nice to look back at where you started, or where you are going!
The Rush Gateway -  Library Gardens: Start your walk under The Rush Gateway. What do the strange shapes on the top mean? 't even think of climbing this as it is huge.
Chancery Lane artwork: Drop by Chancery Lane and see if you can spot these colourful creations! There's local artwork, coffee shops and clothing boutiques to enjoy.
Meet a Chancery Lane resident: Not quite a doggy in the window but you can make friends with this one - he won't bite!
Who do you know?: Take a closer look to see who you might recognise on these walls.

Shamrock Hotel - corner Pall Mall & on St: Built in 1854. The gold miners who came to see a show allegedly threw gold nuggets at the feet of a performer one night. Hotel staff later picked them up as tips! What a great job!
Visitor's Information Centre - 67 Pall Mall: You can find lots of information about things to do here. There are brochures, displays and more. Toilets are available at the rear of the building.

Magistrates' Court , 71 Pall Mall: There are fantastic lions and gargoyles at the front of the Magistrates' Court. How many lions and gargoyles can you see? What are they doing outside the Magistrates' Court?

Conservatory Gardens: Established in 1901 and home to ia's oldest glass hoth, and the sculpture of a man fighting a leopard being bitten by a dog! Water tap is at the rear of the gardens tos Rosalind Park.

Rosalind Park: The creek was an important source of food and water for the Dja Dja Wrung people who lived in this area. This  woodland with River Red Gums became a gold, then converted into a public park.

Chinatown precinct: Once home to the Chinese miners in , this place gives you a taste of Chinese culture and history. It's also a great space to run around and explore! See how many lions and dragons you can find.

Golden Dragon Museum: Dragons are a popular and auspicious mythical creature in Chinese culture. See these fearsome and colourful creatures up close!  Check out the fun activities if you\'re here ng school holidays.
Lotus flower: The Lotus flower is often used as a symbol for purity and truth. Can you find the other giant flowers in the area?
Rosalind Park Fernery: Enjoy the cool air as you walk through the fernery. The River Red Gums here are from the original landscape hundreds of rs ago. Look up and see if you can spot a bat or two!
Rosalind Park - resting stop: There are many shady areas where you can stop and have a rest, or simply run around to explore the area.

Playground - open after school hours: Playground heaven! Slides, climbing decks, fireman's pole, , a sandpit, and a large climbing net! Wheelchair accessible in most areas. There's also a drinking  here.
Cascades  and : A cool spot for birds and people to enjoy the park. Built in the 1880s, the original structures fell apart until it was partially rebuilt in 1997.
Peter the Rabbit: This Rabbit is called Peter. What's Peter looking at? What\'s he thinking? Who put him here? Why? So many interesting questions for a giant rabbit. If only he could talk.
Vintage Trams: If you're lucky you might spot the Vintage Talking Tram Tour. Hop on to join the tour but note that you'll have to stay on till it comes back to this spot again to continue your walk.
Alexandra  - Charing Cross: Imagine having a  named after you. This was named after Alexandra, Princess of Wales whose sons, Princes  and George, attended the opening ceremony on 5 July 1881.
Ice Creamery: Check out the many flavours available here. You can sit outside to enjoy your ice-cream while g other people jealous!
Pennyweight Walk: A free gallery with fantastically colourful artwork by  local artists. Get your fix of street art here.
Information Centre: Open daily daily from 9am to 5pm. There are public toilets, water s, fantastic playgrounds, BBQs and picnic tables near the information centre.
Town history: The history of  and its response to Black Saturday is expressed in words throughout the picnic area and playground. Keep an eye out for murals and images as you explore.
Gallipoli Park: On 7 February 2009, a fire front destroyed nearly all the town's buildings. Some of the residents who survived the fire came to Gallipoli Park before being evacuated the next day.
Into the : The path climbs as you leave , with views to your right and a gully of s ahead. Tourism took off here in 1886 when the railway linked  to the ,  inviting interest.
Look up: As you walk, keep your eyes high to see remnants from the bushfires and signs of new life, closer to the ground at your feet.  has a hidden valley feel, surrounded by mountains at all sides.
Like the lichen: As well as tree ferns and mountain ash, there's also plenty of moss and lichen to admire along this walk. The mostly dark cions suit the mossy blanket well.
Tiny mushrooms: Depending on the season, you might see a mushroom or two, clinging to a tree branch or nestled in the roots below.
Return to : At the end of the trail, you can visit Steavenson Falls and walk back to town the way you came. Enjoy the shade of the tall manna gums before the er tree ferns appear.
New Life: Once back in , see the 2011 sculpture titled, 'New Life' by local artist, Br Torfs. The dcation reads: 'to honour the past and embrace the future'.  Br has a sculpture garden too.
Meteorite Park: Dcated to a meteorite that fell over  on the 28 Sept 1969. See the newspaper clippings from across the globe on display. Fragments of the meteorite are on display in museums around

Gregorys Bridge Hotel: Built 1865 and 1868, it was a country hotel, large general store and cellar with stables at the rear. The tree out front was planted in 1916 and is one of Victorias finest Lon Plane trees.

River bank gardens, boardwalk and three information lecterns: Discover s bygone era with images of the old streetscape, pub and paddle steamers. The boardwalk provides an impressive view of the  River.
River: Saw its first paddle steamer in 1875. At the time  had six hotels, two flour mills and nume stores and services.
Heritage Centre: Located out the side of the museum is a large pump that was used to pump water from the river for the townspeople.
Sparks Reserve : An open space with a playground, sitting area, dog poo bag dispenser and creek-side picnic spot

New path, connecting the  Creek Trail with the Main  Trail: Look left here to see the new path to the Main  Trail, via  Waller Reserve.  This path is due to open to the public in 2017, though it is already well-trodden.
Bridge under  Road : This terrific bridge joined Sparks Reserve with the  Creek Trail, g life much easier for s residents wanting to walk along the creek.
Flood-proof fencing: The  Creek floods regularly - to avoid fence losses, the owners of creek-side properties installed cable-based fencing with pivots with water flow.
A good spot to spot carp: At the annual 'catch-a-carp' day, these pest fishes are sometime spotted here - though rarely caught.
Hill stabilisation works : Build on an old tip, this hill is prone to slipping.  New stabilisation works and planting will keep  in place.
Ivanhoe Wetlands: Look across to the Ivanhoe Wetlands - constructed in 1992, they are a  for birds and wildlife.  You can reach them via paths and stepping stones further along the creek.
Parklands entrance - and 're-bushing': Look to your right for where grass and weeds have been sprayed to make way for new planting - as part of an ongoing parkland-wide transition from grass to bush.
Parklands map: Just next to the path, this map shows the main walking and cycle routes through the parklands, as well as provision for dog-off leash areas and a number of historical markers.

A spot for everyone - seats and nesting boxes: As you stroll through the park, look up to see nest boxes for native birds and small animals - they are an ongoing project of the DCMC and DPA to help wildlife protect their  from predators.
Path to the Ivanhoe Wetlands: Follow this path to the right to find the stepping stones over the creek - then onto the Ivanhoe Wetlands, created in 1992.
Mount Puffalo: Mount Puffalo was created in 1998, and provides superb view of the park.
Not just a duck pond: Part of the parklands is built over a landfill, which 'leaches' liquid - a system on ponds, reed beds, s and wetlands clean and treats the water before it reaches the creek.
- aerating the water: Lovely to look at and listen to, this  plays a key role in the water treatment system - it aerates the water as it travels from one pond to another.
Feng the ducks - tempting, but discged: Ducks love bread, but it's not good for them - while you might not be feng them much, please consider that you may be the tenth visitor today.
On your bike!: There are nume shared trails through the parklands, though this one provides the easiest passage for wheels of all types.
Spend some quality time with the ducks: Seats like this one are dotted throughout the parklands, providing a rest stop and an opportunity to watch the water birds .

school residence,  St: This privately owned cottage was once the residence for Primary School Headmasters. After many rs abned, the current owners have restored its charm.

bushland: Enjoy the natural bush track with local flora and fauna. To the west is the old reservoir, providing water to the township back in the 1800s. The pine trees form a perimeter.

A reminder of  history: This area used to be a mineral quarry.  It closed in the early 1970s as a result of ground water seeping into the quarry hole. The ground water see has produced the lake we see today.
The lake: The b lake is named for its turquoise b colour at certain times of the r and is home to birds including Eurasian coots, Purple Swamphens and asian Grebes.
asian Grebe: They form small fs ng the non-breng season and dive underwater when alarmed.
Lorikeet: Not so hard to spot with their wonderfully coloured feathers,  Lorikeets feed mainly on nectar.  Both male and female Lorikeets feed their .

Laughing Kookaburra: Kookaburras hunt by perching on branches and swooping onto their prey below.  This one has caught a small snack for lunch.  Larger prey like snakes are bashed against branches before being eaten.
Look high and low : This areas environmental vas are of nal and state significance.  All native flora in the area must not be picked.
Sulpher crested Cockatoo: You'll probably hear one before you see one.  Their loud, harsh calls can be heard from quite a distance.  They breed in hollows in old growth trees.
White Cedar: Look for these deciduous trees on the left of the path as you pass the Children's Garden.
Jac: Stop in at the mighty Jac tree on the left. What stage of its annual life cycle is it up to? 't forget to record what you see on the CteWatch app or recording sheet.
Firewheel Tree: This beautiful native tree on your left has striking red flowers. Are they out today?
Flame Tree: An iconic ian tree which flowers in spring. Scientists think that these trees and others might flower earlier due to cte change, so please record what you see.
English Oak: This tree can be quite tricky to find, but if you spot it, record what stage of its annual cycle it is at. Leaves falling? Flowers opening? Submit your sightings on the CteWatch app
: This giant tree is just past the cafe. s aren't related to other oak trees at all but are actually a species of Grevilla and are very popular with birds!
Lake: As you walk around the lake, look for birds. Dusky moorhens, black s, willie wagtails, and many other CteWatch species love this beautiful spot.

Silver  and Victorian Christmas Bush: As the tip of Long nd you will find both of these native plants. Check to see if they are flowering, and be sure to smell the minty leaves of the VIC Christmas Bush
Marri: The last stop on the CteWatch trail is the Western ian Marri eucalypt. Check to see if it is flowering, or whether it is sporting has any gumnuts (known as honky nuts in the west).

Native flowers and bushes: There are plenty of native trees and flowers planted just a few steps back from the beach.  There are a few  areas that are shady and away from the sand if you need refuge from the beach.

Walk, skate or scoot: It's great that the paths for walkers and cyclists are seted for most of the trail. The pedestrian trail is smooth, well maintained and clearly marked.  Or you can simply walk along the beach!
Beach as far as you can see: Beach with a lovely view of the sea. Read a book, have a nap, bring a picnic, build a sandcastle, go for a swim... the possibilities are endless.
Ships ahoy - playground: A fabulous wooden construction that looks like a ship!  Great for kids to cl and explore.  Plenty of shade provided as well.
Information boards: Information boards are great for telling you more about the area - the birds, genous culture, names of local plants etc.
Barraimal () Constellation: The  Constellation according to the Boon Wurrung people. More information available on nearby information boards.
Black s: We saw a pair of canoodling black s!

Middle  Baths: The legendary Ice Berger swimmers swim here. They swim all r around, even in winter! There is also a gym, steam room, cafe and restaurant - all hd in a lovely historic art deco building.
Royal  Yacht Club and dog off lead area: Great view of the yachts from here. This is also a dog off lead area, though off lead times do change depending on the time of r.
Instion chairs: Take a seat and be inspired, reflect and celebrate! A nice touch - each chair has a little plaque with a theme.  This one's The Togetherness Chair
Beach Boxes: The  Beach Boxes are iconic. All painted in bright colours, they're popular with photographers and tourists.  Some of the boxes have wonderful artwork painted on them too.
Mosaic: A few pieces of colourful mosaic can be found here.
Drinks for 2 and 4 legged walkers!: There are plenty of drinking s throughout the walk.
Good spot for a picnic lunch: Table and chairs outside the old angling club, great spot to view the ducks and other water birds
BBQ and Playground: Next to the footy ground is a great playground with BBQ facilities
Heaven for dog walking: There is plenty to keep even the most inquisitive dog occupied along the way.
Careful cng the busy road: Wait for green pedestrian s before cng, 't try to cross this road without the traffic s.
View from bridge: Looking down onto the tranquil river below the busy bridge, makes you wish you were a platypus living in peace.
Wide open spaces:  Park is the perfect spot to run around, kick the footy or simply get away from it all.
Connecting point with other walking tracks: You have lots of choices where to walk from here.
Very cool new  pedestrian bridge: New  pedestrian bridge
Coffee time?: Why not have a break and take the stairs/paths up to one of the many cafes along  Street
Better than any classroom: The local primary school visits the park to help the kids stay active and learn about their beautiful backyard.
Old public swimming Pool: Now it seems to be mainly used by the ducks
What a view!: A sanctuary in the middle of
Choose your own adventure: We picked the est route for this trip as we had a toddler in tow and the sun was getting warm by mid-morning.
View from the top: The view of the surrounding valley is pretty spectacular from here.  The hill is steep so it's a great workout if you need to get your heart rate up.
Extensive revegetation: Since the park was declared in 1972, a great deal of work has been e to restore the genous vegetation to the area. (See Parknotes)
Picnic table and seats: A lovely shady spot for lunch or a cuppa.
The Organ Pipes: More than a million rs ago, lava from nearby volcanoes flowed into the area, cooled, ed, then cracked, forming the columns that we see today.
Popular walk for families with er children: On our visit, we met at least 10 other children, which confirms that the walk is suitable for  ones too.
Exploring s Creek: The shores of the creek is a good spot for  explorers.
View upstream: The creek is cool and shady if you need a break from the heat of the sun.
Start walk at bridge,  Road end, in cwise direction: Notice the lake sign made from red gum.  Timber cutting for firewood was the reason St. Leonards was originally settled by Captain George  Cole.

Opl detour to Mount St Leonards, a  steep walk: From the top there are expansive views over the town, bay and surrounds. 

The hill was formed when the man-made lake was excavated.

Continue along the shaded track & notice the birds : Frequently there is active bird life - swamp hens, coots, cormorants.  Can you hear frogs?  

Distance markers are painted on the track.

Walk past the Sewerage Pump Station & take rest in the shade: Around the bend behind the native trees, the Sewerage Pump takes the town waste to the  Sewerage facility. 

Now you leave the wooded area and walk tos the Recreation Reserve.

Stroll through the 'Len Trewin Reserve': Len secured a 99 r lease when he & others started the cricket club in the 1940's.  A handmade wrought iron sign over an entrance can be seen from the road. 

Public toilets located here.
Pass Cole St Reserve  & Clubrooms: This is a cluster of community facilities for recreation and service activities.  The long anticipated Men's Shed will be here when vations are carried out.
Opl detour to see wetlands: Cross Cole Street with care. Here you will find tennis, bocce and a children's playground.  This area is popular in summer.

Continue along the wng track: This wetland seasonally floods & attracts wading birds such as the Royal Spoonbill, herons & egrets. 

Watch for bike riders.

Cross McBeth St to the Native Flora display board: This board depicts the protected flora species in the Charles McCarthy Oval area.  This oval is used for sports training.

There is a bus shelter here but no seating.

Retrace your steps to rejoin the Lake Track: On the left, notice the Arboretum planted by St. Leonards Primary School in 1981, creating an area of native flora for the benefit of wildlife & the community. 

Pass the rear of the Bowling Club.

Continue along Lake track cwise: Join Murradoc Road, the main access road into St. Leonards.  Geese might greet you here.  The local rule is 'Give way to geese!'
  
The bus stop here has seating.
Follow track along McLeod St: This gives a viewing point to the oval across the lake. Common birds seen here are cormorants, water hens, coots and pelicans.
Notice the picnic facilities for rest, shade & shelter: There are 2 free electric BBQs in the shelter, tables, a playground & toilet facilities.  A convenient place to meet with family and friends.
Close by find an activity area: There is a skate park, basketball/netball rings & a sandpit area.  See the Murals on the Toilet B, part of a community project in 2001.
Finish lake circuit at the bridge: To access the beach and foreshore, leaving the lake, cross  Road with care.  Enjoy water views across Port Philip Bay and activity at the Boat Ramp.

ated land for the building in 1973.

Doongalla : Doongalla  was constructed in 1892 by Sir Matthew Davies, a well known land speculator in the 1880s land boom, who named the property ‘Invermay'. The h burned down in 1932.

: At then end of your walk, check out  the country town of  - well worth a visit.

Weekly walking group on Wednesdays 11.30am.

rocks : Xanthoria Parietina (Common  Lichen) give the granite s their distinctive colour. There is a sow flowing river to cross here.

Track to Little Waterloo Bay Beach: Love this part of the track, but can get a bit  sometimes.

Refuge Cove Campsite: You are here!
Eltham Station underpass: Cross the tracks by going under the gloomy underpass.
The ugly car park: 't be put off by the ugly car park and watch out cng the road!
The path : Walk along Diamond St until you get to the path (gate in the fence), then you are set.
Eltham Central Park: If it's winter, you might even get the chance to stop and watch some local footy.
Eltham Trestle Bridge: The bridge was built in 1901 and is one of the last remaining on the Melbounre train network, it's a beauty!
The : The path snakes around the  (if you are very lucky, you might see a snake in summer).

Railway  cng: The first glimpse of the  Railway is the cng on Main Rd.

South  Station: South  Station is easy accessible from any train as they all stop at South . Our walk start's at South  Station so it is easy to get to.

Red Wattle Bird: If you spot one, notice what it is feng on.  As a honeter it has a highly developed brush-tipped tongue pted for nectar feng.  It also eats es and can catch insects in mid air.
ian Wood Ducks: You are sure to see ian Wood Ducks.  They form monogamous breng pairs that stay together r round. They nest in tree holes, above or near water, often re-using the same site.
Kan Apple: You can't mistake this plants kan paw leaves.  The fruits were eaten by Aboriginal people, but only when very ripe, as they are said to be poisonous at other times.
Red Rump Parrot : Keep your eyes out for Red Rump Parrots.  They spend a great deal of time feng on the ground, and often call to one another.  The male (front) is very colourful.
river: A bstone ford across the river gives you a chance to pause, enjoy the beautiful view, and listen to the sounds of the prolific birdlife.

You are not the first walker here: Archaeological studies have found that the  Park area is among the oldest known human-inhabited sites in ia, with Aboriginal occupation extending back over 40,000 rs.
s Creek: If you are lucky you might spot a long-necked tortoise with its nostrils barely above the sows.  If it hears you, it will submerge for several minutes.

White faced heron (and Eastern egret): The heron feeds on fish, insects and amphibians. You might see it walking to disturb it's prey, searching among damp crevices or simply standing in the water and watching for movement.
Dodd's : The park was operated as farmland by the Dodd family from 1860 to 1974.  This is the original Dodd .

B Box eucalypts: These trees are a botanical anomaly, found only here and in . They are obviously very old

The Old Ford: Supposedly where  and ll crossed the River in 1826.
CWA Gardens: CWA Gardens is home to the towns historic c, originally hd in the historic  Chataeu tower and cellars, built in 1889.
Mount Saddlck: The trail is set at the base of Mount Saddlback. To the South you can see ,  hill to the South East and to the West you will see St. Mary's Church, build in 1998.
Branch line: The branch line to  was constructed by the  Shire in 1890 and taken over by the Victorian Railways in 1892. The railway was closed in 1986 and the rails removed ly after.

Various fauna and flora: including echidnas, b tongue lizzards, kans and even wedge tailed eagles.

Luna Park: Acclaimed as one of the world's oldest amusement parks, Luna Park has been an icon of St Kilda since it was opened in 1912 .
The Palais: Cross Cavell St and wander along the Lower Esplanade.  Generations of  residents have come here to dance, listen to live music and even watch movies.
Arch: Built in 1916, it provides a great place to stop and enjoy the view and is a popular photo spot for g couples.
St Kilda Sea Baths: ou can stop for a swim, spa or seaweed wrap here or grab a bite to eat in one of the cafes or restaurants based here.
Mirka Mora Mosaic: Beautiful mosaic map of St Kilda by Mirka Mora, a Jewish refugee who came to ia to avoid persecution ng World War II.
St Kilda Pier: home of the famous Kirby's Kiosk.  Beyond the kiosk is the  - home to St Kilda's own  colony.  If you keep your eyes open around dusk you may see them swimming home to roost.
Park:  Gardens, where you can stop for a picnic or a BBQ.  If you have the time, take a walk along the Esplanade tos Port .  Look out for kite boarders on the bay.
The Upper Esplanade: The Upper Esplanade, which boasts fantastic views of  Bay.  On Sundays there is an arts and crafts market here.

The Arts Centre spire: The Arts Centre spire taken from the garden of the Nal Gallery of Victoria

Remains of Great Extended Hustler's Reef Goldmine - machinery foundations.: The mine opened in 1865 and closed in 1921. It was a kilometre p and extended outs up to 3 kms be . The remains are the foundations for large mine machinery.

Memorial to the 7 men killed on 2nd May 1914.: In May 2008 the Friends of Hustlers Reef dcated this memorial to the men who died in 1914. In May 2014 the  commemorated the centenary of the disaster with a community history open day.

Box Iron Bark Living Memorial Revegetation.: The Friends of Hustler's Reserve have worked hard to clear invasive weeds,  re-vegetate with local genous plants and reinforce eroded paths re-using existing materials from the site.

Remains of Great Extended Hustler's Reef Gold Mine.: It's undergone a significant clean up since this photo was taken in 2013 & is considerably less spooky. Remains of foundations for boilers, compressors and sidewinders litter the  landscape.
Gentle rise:  is spotted with mul hills covered in  scrub. In late winter they are often ablaze in wattle gold & are always filled with native birds. The  Bird Guide is linked below.

Memorial to Gold Widows.: Situated at the Eastern end of the Reserve is another memorial - this one for the 100’s of widows who lost their husbands through mining accidents or miners phthisis (silicosis).
Boundry Arms Hotel.: Not only does this pub have cold beer and a good feed but there is also a huge range of classic old photos of 's mining heyday available for close inspection.

Beautiful Hs and Incrble Views.: Extend your walk out of the Reserve to follow the curve of  St, and see beautiful old homes and clear views of . If you're able, head into town to climb the Poppet Head in Rosalind Park.

Paper Plane Crash Site.: Sne crashed a huge iron paper plane  into their front yard! The sculpture is a local novelty. No photo out of interest for the hwner's pri but I do recommend a look - kids will love it!

Remember - Frederick James Chinn.: Born in  in 1888 he was the eighth child of Annie Yates and James Chinn. Frederick was 26 rs old and unmarried. He was buried at Kan Flat Cemetery and his headstone can still be viewed.
Remember - William Ryan.: Also 26 and unmarried he left behind his parents John and Jessie.
Remember - William  Blair.: The oldest of those killed in the blast. Born in  he was forty rs old when the explosion widowed his wife Catherine and three children.

Remember - Matthew George Forster.: At 28 Matthew left behind his wife Maud with two children. Although she remarried two rs later and moved to Collingwood, she eventually returned to  to be buried with Matthew.
Remember -  John Thomas.: At 30  was 8 rs er than his father John when he was also killed in an  explosion at Hustler's.  was 15 & had 4 siblings.His wife Ethel was left with 3 children when he died.
Remember -   .:  was 23 and the est of those killed. He was buried with his older brother Murdock who had been killed nine rs earlier aged just 18 at the  United Mine.

Remember - John Henry .: The explosion left 31 r old John's wife widowed with two children and after his death, she delivered their daughter Ida. Margaret went on to bury Ida with John just five rs later.

Poppet Head: This used to be the site where a replica of a poppet head from the mining days was situated. 
It was used for mining Antimony at the Ringwood Antimony mine. A plaque remains.

Miner's Cottage: A replica of a miner's cottage from the days of Antimony mining stood here but was destroyed by fire. 
What remains is a plaque and board providing information.

Main Lake: This is 'Main Lake' it's f large and one of my favourite attraction sites in the sanctuary. You might also spot a duck in there. You might also want to find a small bridge that crosses this lake.

Kensington Railway Station: Originally opened by the  &  Railway Company in 1860, it became a critical transport link for livestock. The signal box was built in 1897, Platform 1 in 1888 & platform 2 in 1905.
H  166-168 Bellair St: ‘’ (1891), was the Kensington Property Exchange. Owned & built by James Wales, a former councillor & mayor in 1899. It was used as a set for the TV show ‘The Sullivans’.

Plumbers H  156 Bellair St: Bill  set up a plumbing business in the 1940s. The only gear he could afford was carried on his bike. By the turn of the century Bill was still here with a workshop out back. The façade remains.

Kuruc H  114 Bellair St: Kuruc H (1898), architects Ussher & Kemp, is an early example of a Queen Anne villa & was occupied by surgeon Joseph Moss until 1910. It continued to be used as a doctor’s clinic until 1973.

Hal Porter H  86 Bellair St: Hal Porter’s memoir "Watcher on the Cast-Iron Balcony" describes his early memories of growing up before WWI at 86 Bellair St, including his walk to Kensington Primary along the cobbled back lanes.

Kensington Town   24 – 40 Bellair St:  & Kensington Town  (1901). Architecturally, it expresses g intentions in a small scale. It became a social hub with dances, gs, women’s groups & an infant welfare centre.

yards (1861-1987)/Now Community High School: By 1888 almost ½ million animals passed annually through the  yards. In the 20th century it became the world’s biggest livestock auction market. Associated industries created many jobs.

6th  Scout   55  St: The 135 r old , at the rear, used by the scouts since the 1920’s was formerly used by both Anglicans and Methodists before either church was built. Restored with community involvement in 2014.

Kensington Primary School: Kensington State School No.2374 opened in 1881 with an initial enrolment of 228 children, which grew to 1,000 by 1898.  In 1914 the State School was the second largest in Victoria.

Christ Church Uniting : The vacant lot is where the original timber Church (1882) stood. This served as Sunday school until burnt down in the 1970’s. Current Church was built 1889, now a combined Anglican and Uniting Church.
Hardiman’s Hotel: The former  Hotel built in the late 1870’s by the Hardiman family. Designed to look like an ocean liner, rebed in the 40’s by Tim Hardiman and vated by new owners in 1998.

Holy Rosary Cic Church: In 1902 the first Holy Rosary Church opened on Derby Street. It was replaced in 1928 by this Church which first celebrated Mass, and was officially opened, on Christmas Day that r.
Holy Rosary Primary School: A Cic primary school, Holy Rosary, opened at the parish  in 1916 and moved to its present location in 1927.
de Streetscape :  de, Kensington is considered to be one of the most desirable streets in . It is very typical of the suburb and its development over the Victorian era.

burrows: There are many  burrows around, but you need to walk at night to see them.

Three Businessmen Who Brought Their Own Lunch: Batman, ston and Hoddle:  These figures by Alison Weaver and Paul Quinn were installed in ston St. the first public sculpture in  since Vault was removed from the  Square in 1981
Time and Tide: Akio Makigawa (born Japan 1948 - died in  1999) has public sculptures in most ian capital cities and several more in .
Architectural Fragment: Petrus Spronk 1992 sculpture is beloved by 's skateboard riders. It is also a fun piece of post-modernism quoting the neo-classical facade of the State Library.
La T: Go La T by Peter Corlett, 2006. This is the only Peter Corlett sculpture on this walk but he has may more around , its suburbs and the rest of the world.
Larry La T: Pam Irving’s bronze dog, “Larry La T” was install in 1993 and stolen in 1995. The current sculpture a new tion cast from the original mould.
Warin: The wooden , “Warin” was carved in situ in 2002 by Des McKenna. Another one for children to climb on.

Loretta Quinn, Beyond the Ocean of Existence, 1993: Loretta Quinn is the brother of Paul Quinn one of the sculptors of The Three Businessmen. Nearby there are painted pole by genous artists, Maree Clarke and Sonja Hodge
and  Monument: This is the fourth location for that this monument has stood in  since 1865. It was originally cast in Charles Summers studio in  St. now the location of Burlington Chs
Street art sculptures in Hosier Lane: Along with all the aerosol art there are some fficial street art sculptures in this lane. You will have to look carefully to find them.
Paul Montford, The Water Nypmh, 1920: Paul Montford brought this sculpture with him when he emigrated to ia in 1923. It was the first public sculpture bought by   Council.
Inge King, For Surge 1972-74: Installed in 1981 this modern fits perfectly into the curved architecture of the Arts Centre and Hamer . The curves also de children who try to climb them.
Matthew  Memorial: The sculptor Charles Web Gilbert, like to do everything himself, from the modelling to the casting of the sculptures.
George VII Memorial: The sculptor  Mackennal was born in Fitzroy but became ia's first internal art star.
The Phoenix: Originally large curved feathers, or flames, were once attached at several points over the body of the sculpture. These have broken off and only fragments of two remain.
The Pathfinder: An tion of English/ian sculptor John  1974 bronze sculpture of a hammer thrower.  Only six rs after this sculpture the   Council installed Vault in the  Square.
Apollo and Hercules: Politician and newspaper proprietor, Theodore Fink  acquired these marble copies of classical sculpture on a holiday in Rome.
Tom , The Genie, 1973: This sculpture is purpose built for children to play on.  sculptor Tom  has several other sculptures around  and at  Ursity.
Vault, Ron rtson-n: In 1980 this sculpture was in the  Square and  was divided by the controversy over this sculpture. In 1981 it was moved to Batman Park by the  River.
The Public Purse,  Simon Perry: In 1994, the  of  added what was described in the design brief as “unique and distinctive forms of street seating” in the streets, The Public Purse was one of them.
The Preston Market: We love the Preston Market because it is really muilti-cultural. There is a great lolly store that sells Amn lollies. It is really cheap place where you can chill out.
Mai Lan Bakery: One of our friend's dad found this bakery in the Age, and it was voted the best pork rolls in . We went there to try something new and they was amazing! They are only $3.50 a roll.
High Street, Preston: This stretch of High St (between  Rd and  St) is really cool. They have all these bargain stores. The vibes you get there are really chill.
Tram Stop to take you down to  Road: We took the 86 tram to get to  Road, the trams go down High Street really often so it is easy to just jump on a tram.
Road Stop Off: Make sure you get off at this tram stop so you can walk down to CERES!
CERES: CERES has a really natural feeling. Anyone can just hang out there. The food is great and the hot chocolates are pretty good, organic too! The markets on Saturdays are really fun too.
Merri Park: Merri Park is fun and right next to  High. There is a cool playground in the park that not bad for teens to hang out on after school hours.
Juline's Noodle Shop: Juline's makes the best chips ever, so addictive! It is like our little community milk bar.
Jump on the 112 tram to take you to Brunswick Street!: There is a tram stop right in front of Juline's Noodle Shop - so really easy to jump on that to take you down to Fitzroy.
Fitzroy Pool: Just down the road from this marker tos Smith Street is our favourite pool. It costs only $2.10 to get in. So cheap and there are never lots of people. They have night sessions too!
Brunswick Street, Fitzroy: We wish that more streets were like Brunswick St. It's got cool clothes shops, 2nd-hand shop called " Gatherer\". Heaps of parks nearby too and cheap food!
San Churros: We finished up our walk at San Churros to re ourselves. It's one of our favourite places to get something yum to eat.
Nal Storage: Striking monochrome throws and characters really brighten up this corner. Be careful of the level cng!
Bowie, Cash and a Cwork  fence: This hwner clearly had a great time in the seventies!
Bowls club: Established in 1864, this bowls club is an institution. Good cold beers at reasonable s too.
Artists Lane: This laneway is overflowing with wow g artworks. Change is the only constant, but keep your eyes ed for works by Mysterious Al, Unwell Bunny, Kaff-eine or Heesco.
Shame Mural and Ming the Merciless: Putos is a prolific artist with a very recognisable style.
Classic Adnate, LucyLucy and Urban Cake Lady: Some classic works that have stuck around for a long while, catch them before they're gone!
Saigon Sally Laneway: A great Asian diner style restaurant with great artwork, inside and out.
Goddess Saraswati: The Hindu goddess of the arts - how appropriate - classic by Deb.

Walking tracks: The walking tracks are mostly level with a few gentle uphill sections.  Some sections are very open.  On a sunny day make sure to bring a hat and a bottle of water.
Butterflies: As you walk in the summer months, hundreds of butterflies will be out, dancing among the shrubs and trees.
Stumpy-tailed  : If you hear a rumble in the grass as you walk you might spot a  out fng a nice spot for sunbaking.
Dilwinia in flower: Dilwinia is just one of many native flowers on the walk that show their true colours ng Spring.

Eastern  Kans: At birth, the infant immately climbs into its mother's pouch and does not emerge for two months. Until they reach 10 or 11 months of age, threatened joeys, will dive for the safety of mom's pouch.
Living Legends: Just in front of the  are real Living Legends! Established to bring retired champion horses back to the public, the front paddocks are home to some of ia's finest retired racehorses.
The Woodlands : Originally imported and erected by the Greene family in 1842, and extended by later owners, the  is a unique example of design, construction and decoration from that era.
A turn in the road: After leaving the , keep an eye out for these posts.  The path turns left up a small incline immately afters.
The parklands: The park contains a landscape that has changed little since pastoral settlement in the 1840s.  Large areas of little-disturbed  woodland provides habitat for kans.

The Eastern : There is a great diversity of birdlife in the park.  Some are easy to spot like the colourful Eastern .  Other tiny birds that nest in bushes near the creek require a little more patience.
Map: At the main car park is a map of the Reserve, giving you a clear overview of your walking options.
The Walking Tracks: Each track is named after one of the birds you’re likely to see on your stroll and it’s clear that the Reserve is being steadily revegetated.
Dog walkers' dise: The Crinigan Reserve is an extremely popular place to indulge your pooch in an enjoyable walk, but please keep your furry friend on a leash at all times.
Cng the water: This boardwalk in the Reserve takes you across waterway and onto Lion’s Dam.
Bring your binoculars: Bird-watching is a well known activity in the Reserve, with a bountiful array of species to spot.
White earned honeter: Found in eastern and southern ia, it lives in dry eucalypt s and woodlands. Find out more and hear its bird call in the link below.
Eastern Spinebill: This gorgeous bird has a long fine and curved bill, with distinctive markings. It is found in eastern and southern ia. Find out more in the link below.
Waxlip Orchid: The Reserve is home to 30 different types of orchids, including this beautiful Waxlip Orchid ( Major). It flowers in late winter to early spring, and is found in heath land and open s.
A world of wetlands: The Lions, Hospital, Wallaby and Tortoise Dams occupy space in this bushland reserve, creating a rich wetland environment.
Rest and relax: You can sit by the water, watch the wildlife and even have a picnic while enjoying the serenity.
Town Pier - now the Port  Yacht Club: Black coal arrived here from . Town Pier was the first significant pier structure in the early settlement of Sandridge. It was demolished in the 1950s.
's Coal Depot: This handsome coal store was one of the businesses owned by William , the first mayor of Sandridge. B stone was preferred to timber as fire was a recurrent danger.
Railway Line: The coal was conveyed by rail pulled by a dray up Dow St. Recent works to create a raingarden revealed the old tram tracks
Sandridge Bay Towers: The former Harpers Starch Factory with its distinctive chimney - a significant landmark through the 20th century.

Esplanade East: The coal continued its journey along Esplanade East - the eastern edge of the former Sandridge Lagoon. It is said that ng the depression, coal would fall from the wagons accidentally on purpose
Gasholders: Huge gasholders stored the gas.  The gas was contained in a huge bell that rested on water. The level would rise up or down, depending on how much was in storage.
The Weighbridge: This is where the coal was brought into the Gasworks and weighed. In the thirties, workers gathered at  in the hope of getting any work at all.
Brick Wall: I love the patterning of this brick wall and the colours in the bricks. Contemplate the size and the length of the walls around Gasworks and imagine them being built brick by brick.
Solar!: Note the solar panels appearing on hs in this neighbourhood. At one time, the Gasworks management had to pay to clean the neighbouring hs from grit and grime.
Softball Reserve: There is lots of room for softball, basll or any other sport
Back on the walking path: Say goodbye to suburbia and hello walking path
Careful cng the road!: Please look both ways before cng  Clarke Road
Car park is accessible off Morang Road: If you choose to drive this is a good parking spot, however why not catch the train and walk from  Train Station which is only 1km away!
Transfer for walking path to footpath: This part of the walk follows the residential streets
Leisure and Services Centre:  Leisure and Services Centre: "...a contemporary aquatics and recreation facilty..."
Mo Drive: This  section of the walk is on the footpath next to Morang Drive
Turn right (south) here!: Turn right here if you which to finish the  Reserve Walk loop
BBQ and covered picnic area: This is a great spot near the playground for a BBQ or picnic with plenty of shade
Plenty of seats for tired legs: Thre are plenty of seats for tired legs all around the loop
Playground: There is a nice playground here which is a perfect spot for the kids to play while you have a breather!
Lots of native flora: There are many native trees planted or protected along the walk. The signs explain what type trees you are looking at.
Continue the loop or go elsewhere: There are plenty of signs to let you know where you are and where you can go. At this point you can leave the loop by heading north or east onto other paths
Residential Street: This section of the walk takes you along a residential street, there are good footpaths  along both side
The Stables Playground: This playground is huge and very cool! Hours of fun for everyone!
Plenty of seats: There are plenty of seats along the way, both shaded and sunny
